{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-af61f3fbe0a94cc0", "type": "tool_result", "content": "<persisted-output>\nOutput too large (73.6KB). Full output saved to: /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/f71cd28a-6202-49ec-8cca-f4b9c49f79eb/tool-results/bihnqljdq.txt\n\nPreview (first 2KB):\nRequirement already satisfied: pymupdf in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (1.27.2.3)\n=== PAGE 1 ===\nJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n1\nPositive-Incentive Noise Predictor for\nAdversarial Purification in Speaker Verification\nYibo Bai, Sizhou Chen, Michele Panariello, Hao Ma, Xiao-Lei Zhang,\nXuelong Li, Massimiliano Todisco, Nicholas Evans\nAbstract—Modern automatic speaker verification (ASV) sys-\ntems are vulnerable to adversarial perturbations. Diffusion-based\npurification has recently shown strong effectiveness against such\nperturbations, but its reverse denoising process requires iterative\nsampling and leads to high inference latency. We find that\nthe forward noising process provides most of the robustness\ngain. Motivated by this observation, we reformulate adversarial\npurification as a learnable noising problem, and propose the\nPositive-Incentive Noise Predictor (PnP), the first framework\nthat explicitly introduces positive-incentive noise (π-noise) into\nthe purification task. PnP learns input-adaptive π-noise and\nmixes it with the input to improve the robustness of downstream\nASV systems. Experiments on four advanced ASV backbones\nshow that PnP effectively defends against adversarial attacks\nwhile preserving performance on natural speech. Compared with\nrepresentative purification baselines, the proposed framework\nprovides a competitive balance among defense effectiveness,\nimpact on genuine utterances, and inference efficiency under\nwhite-box, black-box, and defender-aware adaptive attacks, with\na real-time factor as low as 0.014. Moreover, PnP can be cascaded\nwith a diffusion denoiser to further improve the perceptual\nquality of purified utterances. Code and purified audio examples\nare available at https://eurecom-asp.github.io/pnp/\nIndex Terms—Automatic speaker verification, audio adversar-\nial purification, positive-incentive noise, diffusion model\nI. INTRODUCTION\nA\nUTOMATIC speaker verification (ASV) aims to au-\n...\n</persisted-output>", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "f71cd28a-6202-49ec-8cca-f4b9c49f79eb", "uuid": "f4e88688-ff64-4d30-8e95-c7375c575c7d", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T06:58:52.387Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "Requirement already satisfied: pymupdf in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (1.27.2.3)\n=== PAGE 1 ===\nJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n1\nPositive-Incentive Noise Predictor for\nAdversarial Purification in Speaker Verification\nYibo Bai, Sizhou Chen, Michele Panariello, Hao Ma, Xiao-Lei Zhang,\nXuelong Li, Massimiliano Todisco, Nicholas Evans\nAbstract—Modern automatic speaker verification (ASV) sys-\ntems are vulnerable to adversarial perturbations. Diffusion-based\npurification has recently shown strong effectiveness against such\nperturbations, but its reverse denoising process requires iterative\nsampling and leads to high inference latency. We find that\nthe forward noising process provides most of the robustness\ngain. Motivated by this observation, we reformulate adversarial\npurification as a learnable noising problem, and propose the\nPositive-Incentive Noise Predictor (PnP), the first framework\nthat explicitly introduces positive-incentive noise (π-noise) into\nthe purification task. PnP learns input-adaptive π-noise and\nmixes it with the input to improve the robustness of downstream\nASV systems. Experiments on four advanced ASV backbones\nshow that PnP effectively defends against adversarial attacks\nwhile preserving performance on natural speech. Compared with\nrepresentative purification baselines, the proposed framework\nprovides a competitive balance among defense effectiveness,\nimpact on genuine utterances, and inference efficiency under\nwhite-box, black-box, and defender-aware adaptive attacks, with\na real-time factor as low as 0.014. Moreover, PnP can be cascaded\nwith a diffusion denoiser to further improve the perceptual\nquality of purified utterances. Code and purified audio examples\nare available at https://eurecom-asp.github.io/pnp/\nIndex Terms—Automatic speaker verification, audio adversar-\nial purification, positive-incentive noise, diffusion model\nI. INTRODUCTION\nA\nUTOMATIC speaker verification (ASV) aims to au-\nthenticate users by comparing speaker representations\nextracted from speech signals [1]. As for any biometric errors\nmay cause genuine users to be rejected or impostors to be\naccepted. Recent deep speaker embeddings and large-scale\npretrained speech encoders have substantially advanced ASV\nperformance, including wav2vec 2.0 [2], WavLM [3], and\nWhisper [4]. Despite these advances, state-of-the-art ASV\nsystems remain vulnerable to spoofing and adversarial attacks.\nSpoofing attacks use synthetic or converted speech to imper-\nsonate a target speaker, motivating spoofing countermeasures\nYibo Bai, Michele Panariello, Massimiliano Todisco and Nicholas Evans\nare with the Audio Security and Privacy Group, EURECOM, 06904 Biot,\nFrance (e-mail: yibo.bai@eurecom.fr, michele.panariello@eurecom.fr, massi-\nmiliano.todisco@eurecom.fr, nicholas.evans@eurecom.fr).\nSizhou Chen is with the School of Computer Science, The University of\nSydney, Sydney, NSW 2006, Australia (e-mail: szchen1005@gmail.com).\nHao Ma and Xiao-Lei Zhang are with the School of Marine Sci-\nence and Technology, Northwestern Polytechnical University, Xi’an 710072,\nChina, also with the Institute of Artificial Intelligence (TeleAI), China\nTelecom, P. R. China, and also with the Research and Development Insti-\ntute of Northwestern Polytechnical University in Shenzhen, China (e-mail:\nhaoma@mail.nwpu.edu.cn, xiaolei.zhang@nwpu.edu.cn).\nXuelong Li is with the Institute of Artificial Intelligence (TeleAI), China\nTelecom, P. R. China (e-mail: xuelong li@ieee.org).\nsuch as those developed within the context of ASVspoof\nchallenges [5]. Adversarial attacks instead add small, human-\nimperceptible perturbations to speech signals to manipulate\ndownstream decisions [6].\nAdversarial attacks have been shown to be effective against\nASV systems while maintaining high perceptual quality, often\nwith signal-to-noise ratios (SNRs) above 30 dB [7]. Such\nadversarial perturbations can induce the false rejection of\ngenuine speakers or the false acceptance of impostors. By\noptimizing against the verification objective, adversarial attack\nperturbations are crafted to mislead the target model. Most at-\ntacks are gradient-based [8]–[10] and typically assume white-\nbox access to the victim model. In gray-box or black-box\nsettings, such access to model architecture and parameters is\nlimited or unavailable. In these settings, transfer-based attack\nperturbations are crafted using surrogate models [11], [12] and\nquery-based attack perturbations are optimized with gradient\nestimation [13]. Adversarial threats have also been extended\nto more realistic settings, including streaming input [14], over-\nthe-air scenarios [15], and text-dependent ASV [16].\nRecent defense methods against adversarial attacks have ex-\nplored proactive and passive defenses [17]. Proactive defense\nmodifies the model to improve robustness before deployment.\nFor example, adversarial training incorporates adversarial ex-\namples during training [18], which requires generating adver-\nsarial examples and retraining for each target ASV model.\nPassive defense includes adversarial example detection and\nadversarial purification. The former aims to distinguish gen-\nuine inputs from adversarial utterances. For example, learnable\nmask detector (LMD) [19] masks selected time-frequency\nregions and compares embedding similarity differences be-\nfore and after masking to detect adversarial examples. Self-\nsupervised models have also been applied to both detection and\npurification [20]. Mask diffusion detector (MDD) [21] masks\nthe Mel-spectrogram and uses a diffusion model to reconstruct\nmasked regions. However, in detection-based methods, such\nreconstructed outputs are often too distorted for subsequent\nASV scoring, and the detection threshold may vary across\nmodels or input distributions.\nThis paper focuses on adversarial purification, which pas-\nsively processes every input to suppress potential adversarial\nperturbations and maintain performance on genuine utterances.\nEarly purification approaches used simple signal processing,\nsuch as filtering [22] or additive noise [23], but may eas-\nily degrade perceptual quality. More recently, neural audio\ncodecs have been explored as purifiers, as their compres-\nsion and decompression processes can remove adversarial\narXiv:2607.00899v1  [eess.AS]  1 Jul 2026\n\n\n=== PAGE 2 ===\nJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n2\n(a) Diffusion-based purification\n(b) PnP\n𝑥2\n𝑥0\n𝑥1\n𝜋−noise\nObservation:\nForward noising \ndominates robustness\n……\nForward (Noising)\nReverse (Denoising)\n𝑥2\n𝑥0\n𝑥1\n𝑥𝑇\nPurification path\nFig. 1. From diffusion-based purification to PnP. Diffusion models for generative tasks perform a full forward process from x0 to xT , followed by reverse\nsampling back to x0. In contrast, diffusion-based purification only relies on a partial forward and reverse process (an example of x0 →x2 →x0 is highlighted\nin green). Motivated by the observation that most robustness gains actually come from the forward process, PnP reformulates purification as a learned forward\nnoising procedure with task-beneficial positive-incentive noise (π-noise). The right part shows the diffusion-style PnP variant.\nperturbations [24]. Generative approaches have also shown\nstrong performance. Diffusion-based adversarial purification\n(DAP) [25] was the first to introduce diffusion models for\nASV purification, and textual-driven adversarial purification\n(TDAP) [26] further adds text conditioning into the purifi-\ncation process. Despite their strong defense performance,\ndiffusion-based purification methods typically require step-\nby-step sampling, which leads to high latency. Two-stage\ndiffusion-based purification (TDP) [27] improves efficiency by\npurifying in a Mel-spectrogram latent space, but still relies on\na vocoder to reconstruct waveforms, which degrades audio\nquality. Compared with proactive and detection-based passive\ndefenses, purification is more attractive in few-shot or zero-\nshot settings since it does not require model modification or\nthreshold calibration.\nA diffusion-based purifier consists of two stages. The for-\nward noising process gradually corrupts the input toward pure\nGaussian noise, and the reverse denoising process iteratively\npredicts and removes the injected noise. From this viewpoint,\nthe forward noising process alone is conceptually close to\nadditive-noise defense methods [23], which also perturb the\ninput with noise of fixed standard deviation. This observation\nnaturally raises a question: is the reverse denoising process\nnecessary for effective adversarial purification?\nIf most robustness gains already come from forward noising,\nadversarial purification for ASV can instead be reformulated as\na learned forward noising problem, rather than relying on a full\ndiffusion-based purification pipeline. Our preliminary experi-\nments support this hypothesis. Motivated by this observation,\nwe propose a unified input-adaptive Positive-Incentive Noise\nPredictor (PnP) framework, which learns task-beneficial noise\nas a front-end purification module for speaker verification.\nFig. 1 illustrates this shift in perspective. Instead of relying\non reverse denoising, we focus on the forward process and\ninvestigate whether the injected noise can be learned to be\ntask-beneficial. Under this framework, PnP-Gaussian pro-\nvides a simple additive formulation, while PnP-Diff provides\na diffusion-style formulation aligned with the forward noising\nprocess of a diffusion model. Moreover, the diffusion-style\nvariant can be optionally cascaded with a diffusion denoiser\nfor audio quality enhancement.\nThe main contributions are summarized below.\n• We revisit diffusion-based audio adversarial purification\nand show that robustness gains come largely from the\nforward noising process rather than the more expensive\nreverse denoising process. This provides a new perspec-\ntive for simplifying diffusion-based defenses in ASV.\n• Based on this observation, we propose the first frame-\nwork that uses positive-incentive noise (π-noise) in the\nadversarial purification task. Our PnP method learns\ninput-adaptive π-noise as a front-end purifier for ASV.\nWithin this unified framework, PnP-Gaussian serves as\nan adaptive version of additive noising, while PnP-Diff\nreplaces the fixed Gaussian forward noise in diffusion\npurification with learned π-noise.\n• Extensive experiments show that the proposed framework\nconsistently improves adversarial robustness in ASV un-\nder white-box, black-box, and defender-aware adaptive\nattacks. The 1-step and 2-step PnP-Diff variants achieve\nstate-of-the-art robustness across different attack settings\nwith a real-time factor (RTF) of 0.014. In addition,\ncascading PnP-Diff with a diffusion denoiser further im-\nproves perceptual quality, reaching a WB-PESQ of 3.591\nand an SI-SDR of 21.14 dB on adversarial VoxCeleb data.\nII. BACKGROUND\nA. Automatic Speaker Verification\nAn ASV system aims to verify the speaker identity of\nan input test utterance xtest. Given a pair of waveforms\n(xtest, xenroll), where xenroll is an enrollment utterance from a\nknown speaker, the ASV system extracts speaker embeddings\nand computes a similarity score s(xtest, xenroll) between them.\nThe verification decision is made by comparing the similarity\nscore with a threshold.\nCommon ASV embedding extractors include x-vector [28],\nECAPA-TDNN [29], and ResNet-based encoders [30]. These\nsystems typically take logarithmic filterbanks (LogFBank) as\ninput. Recently, self-supervised learning (SSL) speech models\nsuch as wav2vec 2.0 [2] and WavLM [3] have also been\nadopted as upstream feature extractors, replacing conventional\nLogFBank features [31].\nB. Adversarial attacks in ASV\nAdversarial attacks were first introduced in the image clas-\nsification domain [6]. Despite appearing visually similar to\noriginal genuine examples, adversarial images can mislead\nwell-trained classifiers. Such examples are typically crafted\n\n\n=== PAGE 3 ===\nJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n3\nto cross the classification boundary while being constrained\nby an ℓp norm to remain imperceptible. Subsequent works\nproposed stronger optimization-based attacks and robustness\nevaluations, such as FGSM [8], PGD [10], and CW [32]. These\nattacks can be conducted in a white-box setting, where the\nattacker has full model knowledge, or in a black-box setting,\nwhere the attacker has no access to the internal parameters of\nthe target model and may then rely on either transfer-based or\nquery-based methods.\nIn the ASV setting, the attacker aims to craft a perturbed\nadversarial test utterance xadv = xtest + δ with extremely\nsmall ∥δ∥p. Although xadv still sounds identical to xtest, it\nmay cause false accepts for unauthorized speakers or false\nrejects for genuine speakers.\nIn this paper, we consider MI-FGSM [33] and PGD [10] as\ntwo strong, gradient-based attacks.\n1) MI-FGSM:\nMomentum iterative fast gradient sign\nmethod (MI-FGSM) is an iterative ℓ∞attack with momentum.\nLet J (x) denote the attack objective. Starting from x0 = xtest\nand g0 = 0, MI-FGSM iterates\ngk+1 = µ gk +\n∇xJ (xk)\n∥∇xJ (xk)∥1\n,\n(1)\nxk+1 = ΠB∞(xk + α · sign(gk+1)) ,\n(2)\nwhere α is the step size, µ is the momentum decay, and ΠBp(·)\ndenotes the projection onto a norm sphere ℓp that constrains\nthe perturbation magnitude.\n2) PGD: Projected gradient descent (PGD) is a multi-step\nfirst-order attack with projection. Let J (x) denote the attack\nobjective. In our experiments, we evaluate PGD-ℓ∞and PGD-\nℓ2 attacks under different types of norm constraints. Starting\nfrom x0 = xtest, PGD iterates\nPGD-ℓ∞:\nxk+1 = ΠB∞(xk + α · sign(∇xJ (xk))) , (3)\nPGD-ℓ2 :\nxk+1 = ΠB2\n\u0012\nxk + α ·\n∇xJ (xk)\n∥∇xJ (xk)∥2\n\u0013\n.\n(4)\nC. Diffusion-based purification\nTo protect models from adversarial attacks, purification\nmethods aim to remove adversarial perturbations from the\ninput. DiffPure [34] was first proposed to defend image\nclassifiers with pretrained diffusion models. As a diffusion\nmodel consists of a forward noising process and a reverse\ndenoising process, given an input sample x0, the forward\nprocess can be formulated as\nxt = √¯αt x0 +\n√\n1 −¯αt ϵ,\n(5)\nwhere ϵ ∼N(0, I) is a Gaussian noise and ¯αt at step t\nis computed by a predefined noise schedule. In the reverse\nprocess, the diffusion model is trained to predict an esti-\nmated noise ϵθ to remove this noise step by step. Given\nan adversarial input xadv and a chosen purification step t∗,\nDiffPure applies the forward process to obtain xadv\nt∗\nbefore\nthe reverse process. AudioPure [35] subsequently applies this\nidea to adversarial audio for speech emotion classification. In\nthe ASV domain, unlike DiffPure and AudioPure, DAP [25]\nis trained on adversarial data and runs the full reverse process\n1\n2\n3\nForward diffusion step t *\n4.0\n4.5\n5.0\n5.5\n6.0\n6.5\n7.0\nPurified Adv. EER (%)\nAudioPure (Forward + reverse)\nAudioPure (Forward stage only)\nFig. 2.\nMethod motivation from diffusion purification analysis. In this\npreliminary experiment, we compare the purified adversarial EERs of two\nAudioPure-based purifiers under 50-step MI-FGSM attack, including the\nfull AudioPure purifier with forward noising plus reverse denoising and its\nforward-stage-only purifier variant. The small gap between the two curves\nindicates that forward noising already provides most of the robustness.\ndirectly on xadv rather than xadv\nt∗, which yields better audio\nquality for purified utterances but requires extra inference\ntime; additionally, DAP requires large-scale adversarial audio.\nSample-specific noise injection (SSNI) [36] further replaces\nthe shared purification level t∗with a sample-specific t(x)\nestimated from the score magnitude of a pretrained diffusion\nmodel. SSNI is similar to our work in that it also questions the\nuse of a fixed forward noising process. However, SSNI still\nassumes Gaussian noise in the forward process and retains\nthe reverse denoising procedure, whereas our PnP framework\nlearns task-beneficial noise and makes the denoiser optional.\nIII. POSITIVE-INCENTIVE NOISE PREDICTOR FOR ASV\nADVERSARIAL PURIFICATION\nThis section first motivates the Positive-Incentive Noise\nPredictor (PnP) through a preliminary experiment in Sec-\ntion III-A. Section III-B then introduces the unified PnP\nframework and its learning objective. Section III-C presents\nits applications to adversarial purification.\nA. Motivation from Diffusion-Based Purification\nAdversarial purification protects a downstream ASV model\nfrom the influence of adversarial perturbations. By revisit-\ning the diffusion-based purification pipeline through AudioP-\nure [35], we investigate whether most robustness gains already\narise from the forward noising stage. In particular, we compare\nthe defense performance of the full AudioPure pipeline with\nits forward-process-only variant on VoxCeleb1 data attacked\nby MI-FGSM. As shown in Fig. 2, the forward-only variant\nachieves purified adversarial EERs that are very close to those\nof the full pipeline across different forward diffusion steps.\nMore detailed stepwise analysis of AudioPure is provided\nin Section V-B. This motivates us to learn a task-beneficial\nforward noising process, which we formulate next through a\npositive-incentive learning objective.\n\n\n=== PAGE 4 ===\nJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n4\nASV\n(Frozen)\nGenuine Consistency\nAlign ො𝑥gen with 𝑥gen\nAdversarial Recovery\nAlign ො𝑥adv with 𝑥gen\nPositive-Incentive Objective (ℒrobust)\n𝑥gen\n𝑥adv\nො𝑥gen\nො𝑥adv\n+𝛿\nPnP\nFig. 3. Training pipeline of the proposed positive-incentive noise predictor (PnP). For each input genuine utterance xgen, we generate its adversarial example\nxadv = xgen + δ. PnP processes the genuine and adversarial inputs, and produces purified outputs ˆxgen and ˆxadv, which are then fed into a frozen ASV\nsystem. The PnP parameters are optimized to increase speaker similarity between the genuine reference and the purified outputs from both branches, thereby\npreserving performance on unattacked inputs while suppressing adversarial perturbations.\nB. Unified PnP Framework\nWe now introduce the unified waveform-level framework\nfor ASV adversarial purification and its learning objective.\nPrevious additive-noise defenses [23] and diffusion-based\npurification methods [35] commonly rely on task-agnostic\nrandom noising. In contrast, PnP replaces this random noising\nwith a learnable positive-incentive noising process.\n1) Framework: Fig. 3 illustrates the implementation of the\nASV-guided PnP framework. Given an input waveform x, PnP\npredicts input-adaptive positive-incentive noise (π-noise) and\ncombines it with the input to construct a purified waveform ˆx\nfor downstream ASV scoring. Unlike ordinary random noise,\nπ-noise benefits a target task, as it is expected to reduce the\nuncertainty of the downstream task rather than simply corrupt\nthe input [37]. In our ASV purification setting, this means\nthat the learned noise should encourage the purified waveform\nto preserve speaker information while suppressing adversarial\nperturbations.\nSpecifically, we construct a learnable noise predictor εω by\ncombining a normalized directional component predicted by a\n1-D U-Net ˜ε with Gaussian noise:\nεω(x) = λ\n˜ε(x)\n∥˜ε(x)∥2\n+\np\n1 −λ2 ϵ,\n(6)\nwhere ϵ ∼N(0, I) and λ ∈[0, 1] controls the mixture ratio.\nTo incorporate the predicted π-noise into the input wave-\nform for purification, we adopt a unified weighted mixing\nformulation:\nˆx = wx x + wn εω(x),\n(7)\nwhere ˆx denotes the purified waveform, and wx and wn control\nthe contributions of the original signal x and the predicted\nnoise εω(x), respectively. Different choices of wx and wn\nlead to different PnP variants, as introduced in Section III-C.\nThe complete procedures are summarized in three algorithms.\nAlgorithm 1 trains the π-noise predictor guided by a frozen\nASV system. Algorithm 2 deploys the trained predictor as\na lightweight pre-processing module. Algorithm 3 further\ndescribes how to train a diffusion denoiser with PnP-generated\nπ-noise for the optional cascade.\n2) Positive-Incentive Learning Objective: We next formal-\nize the positive-incentive learning objective used to train PnP.\nIn the original formulation, π-noise is defined as a noise vari-\nable that reduces the uncertainty of the downstream task. For\na task T , this means that after introducing a π-noise variable\nε, the task becomes more predictable, i.e., H(T | ε) < H(T ),\nwhere H(·) denotes information entropy. If ε does not change\nthe task uncertainty, i.e., H(T\n| ε) = H(T ), then it can\nbe regarded as pure noise. The variational positive-incentive\nnoise (VPN) formulation [38] further shows that this positive-\nincentive objective can be optimized through a variational\nlower bound.\nIn ASV adversarial purification, this perspective is applied\nthrough two directions. The learned noise in PnP should guide\nboth genuine and adversarial inputs in a way that benefits\ndownstream ASV decisions better than random noise. For gen-\nuine inputs, PnP should preserve the verification performance\nof a well-trained ASV system. For adversarial inputs, PnP\nshould suppress adversarial perturbations so that the purified\nadversarial input moves back toward the genuine reference in\nthe speaker embedding space.\nWe instantiate the positive-incentive formulation in the ASV\nsetting as follows. Let T denote the speaker verification task,\nx denote an input utterance, and y ∈[−1, 1] denote the ASV\nverification score. We represent the task by the continuous\nscore y with density p(y | x), and define the task entropy as\nH(T | x) = Ex\nh\n−\nZ\np(y | x) log p(y | x) dy\ni\n.\n(8)\nLet ε be a noise variable sampled from the distribution\nDω(x, y) parameterized by ω. By definition, the mutual in-\nformation between T and ε is\nI(T , ε | x) = Ex Eε\nh Z\np(y, ε | x) log\np(y, ε | x)\np(y | x) p(ε | x) dy\ni\n.\n(9)\nTherefore, if I(T , ε | x) > 0, the noise variable ε\nbecomes positive-incentive noise for task T . Following the\nVPN formulation [38], we optimize a variational lower bound\nof I(T , ε | x). For ASV adversarial purification, we consider\npaired genuine and adversarial inputs in each mini-batch,\n\n\n=== PAGE 5 ===\nJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n5\ndenoted by {(xgen\ni\n, xadv\ni\n)}B\ni=1, and expand the variational\nlower bound over the two branches as\nLπ ≈1\nB\nB\nX\ni=1\nEε\n\u0002\nlog q(yi | xgen\ni\n, ε)\n\u0003\n+ 1\nB\nB\nX\ni=1\nEε\n\u0002\nlog q(yi | xadv\ni\n, ε)\n\u0003\n,\n(10)\nwhere q(y | x, ε) is a variational approximation to p(y | x, ε),\nand we assume that Dω(x, y) is Gaussian. Since xadv\ni\nis\nderived from xgen\ni\n, in practice we parameterize the noise\ngenerator using the genuine and adversarial inputs, i.e.,\nDω(xgen, xadv), rather than explicitly relying on the value of\ny.\nThe two terms in Lπ correspond to the two desired effects\nof PnP, preserving ASV performance for genuine inputs and\nsuppressing adversarial perturbations for adversarial inputs.\nIdeally, the π-noise predictor εω should maximize these two\nvariational terms. However, directly estimating the variational\ndensity q(y | x, ε) is difficult in ASV, since the output\nis a verification score rather than an explicit probabilistic\ndistribution. We therefore use ASV scores as a task-driven\nsurrogate for the positive-incentive objective. Specifically, we\nmaximize the similarity between the genuine reference and\nboth purified genuine and adversarial outputs. A hinge margin\nprevents unnecessary optimization once the similarity score is\nsufficiently high. Other surrogate formulations could also be\nused to optimize the same objective.\nAs shown in Fig. 3, during PnP training, we first generate\nxadv for a given xgen, and then compute ˆxgen and ˆxadv with\nEq. (7). We enforce high speaker similarity between the clean\nreference xgen and the two purified outputs, ˆxgen and ˆxadv,\nby minimizing the high-margin hinge loss:\nLrobust = ϕm\n\u0000s(xgen, ˆxgen)\n\u0001\n+ ϕm\n\u0000s(xgen, ˆxadv)\n\u0001\n,\n(11)\nwhere ϕm(s) = max(0, m −s) with m chosen close to 1.\nTo regularize the magnitude of the learned π-noise, we\npenalize the energy:\nLreg = ∥εω(xgen)∥2\n2 +\n\r\rεω(xadv)\n\r\r2\n2 .\n(12)\nThe overall training loss is then given by:\nL(ω) = Lrobust + γLreg,\n(13)\nwhere γ > 0 is a weighting coefficient. Algorithm 1 summa-\nrizes the training procedure.\nDuring the test stage, we deploy the trained PnP as a pre-\nprocessing purification module in front of an ASV system.\nGiven a test utterance x, PnP predicts task-beneficial noise\nand mixes it with the input according to Eq. (6) and Eq. (7)\nto suppress potential adversarial perturbations. Algorithm 2\nsummarizes the inference procedure.\nC. Applications to Adversarial Purification\nBased on the unified mixing formulation in Eq. (7), PnP\ncan be instantiated by choosing different weights for the input\nwaveform and the predicted π-noise. We consider two basic\nstandalone variants for ASV adversarial purification, namely\nAlgorithm 1 Train a positive-incentive noise predictor with a\nfrozen ASV system\nInput: Training set {(xgen\ni , xadv\ni )}n\ni=1, batch size B, and a\nfrozen ASV system.\nOutput: Trained π-noise predictor εω.\n1: Initialize εω.\n2: for each sampled mini-batch {(xgen\ni , xadv\ni )}B\ni=1 do\n3:\nfor each (xgen\ni , xadv\ni ) do\n4:\nGenerate\nπ-noise\nεω(xgen\ni\n)\nand\nεω(xadv\ni\n)\nwith\nEq. (6).\n5:\nObtain purified utterances ˆxgen\ni\nand ˆxadv\ni\nwith Eq. (7).\n6:\nend for\n7:\nCompute Lrobust with the frozen ASV system with\nEq. (11), and compute Lreg with Eq. (12).\n8:\nUpdate εω by minimizing L(ω) = Lrobust + γLreg.\n9: end for\nAlgorithm 2 Purify a test sample with a trained positive-\nincentive noise predictor.\nInput: Trained π-noise predictor εω and test sample x.\nOutput: Purified sample ˆx.\n1: Predict the π-noise εω(x) according to Eq. (6).\n2: Compute the purified sample ˆx by Eq. (7).\n3: Return ˆx for downstream ASV scoring.\nPnP-Gaussian and PnP-Diff. In addition, PnP-Diff can be\noptionally cascaded with a diffusion denoiser as an extension\nfor further processing.\n1) PnP-Gaussian: When wx = wn = 1, PnP reduces to\nsimply adding the learned noise to the original input:\nˆx = x + εω(x).\n(14)\nWe refer to this simplest variant as PnP-Gaussian.\n2) PnP-Diff: In vanilla diffusion models, the forward pro-\ncess is a Markov chain that gradually corrupts the input\nby combining the clean signal and Gaussian noise with\ncoefficients determined by a noise schedule. Motivated by\nthis formulation, we define a diffusion-style variant, PnP-\nDiff, which aligns PnP with the diffusion forward process.\nSpecifically, we set the weights wx and wn according to the\nstandard cumulative diffusion noise schedule {¯αt}, where √¯αt\nand √1 −¯αt weight the signal and noise terms, respectively.\nThe PnP-Diff output at timestep t is then given by\nˆx = √¯αt x +\n√\n1 −¯αt εω(x, t).\n(15)\nCompared with PnP-Gaussian, PnP-Diff explicitly follows\nthe diffusion noise schedule and can therefore be combined\nnaturally with a diffusion reverse process starting from ˆx.\n3) Optional diffusion denoiser cascade: PnP-Diff supports\nan optional extension in which its forward output is further\nprocessed by a diffusion denoiser. This denoiser can be either\na pretrained model or a model retrained with PnP-generated\nπ-noise.\nFor this cascade, we treat the PnP-Diff output as a diffusion-\nstyle corrupted sample, since it follows the same noise sched-\nule as the standard diffusion forward process. In this case,\n\n\n=== PAGE 6 ===\nJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n6\nAlgorithm 3 Train a diffusion model with PnP-generated π-\nnoise\nInput: Trained PnP-Diff generator εω, training utterances\n{xi}n\ni=1, batch size B, maximum diffusion timestep T.\nOutput: Diffusion model ϵθ.\n1: Initialize ϵθ.\n2: for each sampled mini-batch {xi}B\ni=1 do\n3:\nSample timesteps ti ∼Uniform{1, . . . , T} for i =\n1, . . . , B.\n4:\nfor each xi in the mini-batch do\n5:\nGenerate π-noise εi = εω(xi, ti).\n6:\nForm the corrupted sample xt,i from xi and εi\naccording to Eq. (15).\n7:\nend for\n8:\nCompute the diffusion loss 1\nB\nPB\ni=1\n\r\rεi−ϵθ(xt,i, ti)\n\r\r2\n2.\n9:\nUpdate θ by minimizing the diffusion loss.\n10: end for\nas shown in Algorithm 3, we use xt rather than ˆx to denote\nthe mixture of x and εω(x, t), so that it aligns better with\nthe diffusion model. Specifically, PnP-Diff replaces Gaussian\nnoise in the diffusion forward process with learned π-noise\nεω(x, t), and constructs xt according to Eq. (15). This allows\na diffusion reverse process to be applied after the PnP-Diff\nforward step for further quality enhancement.\nOn top of this PnP-driven forward process, we can then\nretrain a diffusion denoiser ϵθ(xt, t) to predict the injected\nπ-noise. The diffusion model loss is formulated as\nLdiff = Ex, t Eεω(x,t)\nh\r\rεω(x, t) −ϵθ(xt, t)\n\r\r2\n2\ni\n.\n(16)\nThis loss function encourages the reverse process to remove\nthe PnP-generated π-noise. Algorithm 3 summarizes the cor-\nresponding training procedure.\nIV. EXPERIMENTAL SETTINGS\nA. Datasets\nWe conduct most of experiments on the VoxCeleb bench-\nmarks [39], [40]. VoxCeleb1 and VoxCeleb2 dataset are\nextracted from YouTube videos and include thousands of\nspeakers. To train the ASV backbones, we follow common\nprotocol and use the full VoxCeleb2 dataset, except pretrained\nSimAMResNet using VoxBlink2 [41]. The VoxCeleb1 devel-\nopment subset of is used to train the proposed PnP methods\nwith VoxCeleb1-E trial list.\nWe evaluate adversarial attack and defense performance\nover 4,000 paired verification trials from VoxCeleb1 test\nset. To balance computational cost and generalizability, we\nconstruct this subset by randomly sampling 50 non-target\ntrials and 50 target trials for each enrollment speaker from\nthe VoxCeleb1-O trial list. In addition, because there are\nno transcriptions for VoxCeleb dataset, 1,000 utterances are", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false, "persistedOutputPath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/f71cd28a-6202-49ec-8cca-f4b9c49f79eb/tool-results/bihnqljdq.txt", "persistedOutputSize": 75397}}
