{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bf92e43e78f96bf1", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tRequirement already satisfied: pymupdf in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (1.27.2.3)\n2\t=== PAGE 1 ===\n3\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n4\t1\n5\tPositive-Incentive Noise Predictor for\n6\tAdversarial Purification in Speaker Verification\n7\tYibo Bai, Sizhou Chen, Michele Panariello, Hao Ma, Xiao-Lei Zhang,\n8\tXuelong Li, Massimiliano Todisco, Nicholas Evans\n9\tAbstract—Modern automatic speaker verification (ASV) sys-\n10\ttems are vulnerable to adversarial perturbations. Diffusion-based\n11\tpurification has recently shown strong effectiveness against such\n12\tperturbations, but its reverse denoising process requires iterative\n13\tsampling and leads to high inference latency. We find that\n14\tthe forward noising process provides most of the robustness\n15\tgain. Motivated by this observation, we reformulate adversarial\n16\tpurification as a learnable noising problem, and propose the\n17\tPositive-Incentive Noise Predictor (PnP), the first framework\n18\tthat explicitly introduces positive-incentive noise (π-noise) into\n19\tthe purification task. PnP learns input-adaptive π-noise and\n20\tmixes it with the input to improve the robustness of downstream\n21\tASV systems. Experiments on four advanced ASV backbones\n22\tshow that PnP effectively defends against adversarial attacks\n23\twhile preserving performance on natural speech. Compared with\n24\trepresentative purification baselines, the proposed framework\n25\tprovides a competitive balance among defense effectiveness,\n26\timpact on genuine utterances, and inference efficiency under\n27\twhite-box, black-box, and defender-aware adaptive attacks, with\n28\ta real-time factor as low as 0.014. Moreover, PnP can be cascaded\n29\twith a diffusion denoiser to further improve the perceptual\n30\tquality of purified utterances. Code and purified audio examples\n31\tare available at https://eurecom-asp.github.io/pnp/\n32\tIndex Terms—Automatic speaker verification, audio adversar-\n33\tial purification, positive-incentive noise, diffusion model\n34\tI. INTRODUCTION\n35\tA\n36\tUTOMATIC speaker verification (ASV) aims to au-\n37\tthenticate users by comparing speaker representations\n38\textracted from speech signals [1]. As for any biometric errors\n39\tmay cause genuine users to be rejected or impostors to be\n40\taccepted. Recent deep speaker embeddings and large-scale\n41\tpretrained speech encoders have substantially advanced ASV\n42\tperformance, including wav2vec 2.0 [2], WavLM [3], and\n43\tWhisper [4]. Despite these advances, state-of-the-art ASV\n44\tsystems remain vulnerable to spoofing and adversarial attacks.\n45\tSpoofing attacks use synthetic or converted speech to imper-\n46\tsonate a target speaker, motivating spoofing countermeasures\n47\tYibo Bai, Michele Panariello, Massimiliano Todisco and Nicholas Evans\n48\tare with the Audio Security and Privacy Group, EURECOM, 06904 Biot,\n49\tFrance (e-mail: yibo.bai@eurecom.fr, michele.panariello@eurecom.fr, massi-\n50\tmiliano.todisco@eurecom.fr, nicholas.evans@eurecom.fr).\n51\tSizhou Chen is with the School of Computer Science, The University of\n52\tSydney, Sydney, NSW 2006, Australia (e-mail: szchen1005@gmail.com).\n53\tHao Ma and Xiao-Lei Zhang are with the School of Marine Sci-\n54\tence and Technology, Northwestern Polytechnical University, Xi’an 710072,\n55\tChina, also with the Institute of Artificial Intelligence (TeleAI), China\n56\tTelecom, P. R. China, and also with the Research and Development Insti-\n57\ttute of Northwestern Polytechnical University in Shenzhen, China (e-mail:\n58\thaoma@mail.nwpu.edu.cn, xiaolei.zhang@nwpu.edu.cn).\n59\tXuelong Li is with the Institute of Artificial Intelligence (TeleAI), China\n60\tTelecom, P. R. China (e-mail: xuelong li@ieee.org).\n61\tsuch as those developed within the context of ASVspoof\n62\tchallenges [5]. Adversarial attacks instead add small, human-\n63\timperceptible perturbations to speech signals to manipulate\n64\tdownstream decisions [6].\n65\tAdversarial attacks have been shown to be effective against\n66\tASV systems while maintaining high perceptual quality, often\n67\twith signal-to-noise ratios (SNRs) above 30 dB [7]. Such\n68\tadversarial perturbations can induce the false rejection of\n69\tgenuine speakers or the false acceptance of impostors. By\n70\toptimizing against the verification objective, adversarial attack\n71\tperturbations are crafted to mislead the target model. Most at-\n72\ttacks are gradient-based [8]–[10] and typically assume white-\n73\tbox access to the victim model. In gray-box or black-box\n74\tsettings, such access to model architecture and parameters is\n75\tlimited or unavailable. In these settings, transfer-based attack\n76\tperturbations are crafted using surrogate models [11], [12] and\n77\tquery-based attack perturbations are optimized with gradient\n78\testimation [13]. Adversarial threats have also been extended\n79\tto more realistic settings, including streaming input [14], over-\n80\tthe-air scenarios [15], and text-dependent ASV [16].\n81\tRecent defense methods against adversarial attacks have ex-\n82\tplored proactive and passive defenses [17]. Proactive defense\n83\tmodifies the model to improve robustness before deployment.\n84\tFor example, adversarial training incorporates adversarial ex-\n85\tamples during training [18], which requires generating adver-\n86\tsarial examples and retraining for each target ASV model.\n87\tPassive defense includes adversarial example detection and\n88\tadversarial purification. The former aims to distinguish gen-\n89\tuine inputs from adversarial utterances. For example, learnable\n90\tmask detector (LMD) [19] masks selected time-frequency\n91\tregions and compares embedding similarity differences be-\n92\tfore and after masking to detect adversarial examples. Self-\n93\tsupervised models have also been applied to both detection and\n94\tpurification [20]. Mask diffusion detector (MDD) [21] masks\n95\tthe Mel-spectrogram and uses a diffusion model to reconstruct\n96\tmasked regions. However, in detection-based methods, such\n97\treconstructed outputs are often too distorted for subsequent\n98\tASV scoring, and the detection threshold may vary across\n99\tmodels or input distributions.\n100\tThis paper focuses on adversarial purification, which pas-\n101\tsively processes every input to suppress potential adversarial\n102\tperturbations and maintain performance on genuine utterances.\n103\tEarly purification approaches used simple signal processing,\n104\tsuch as filtering [22] or additive noise [23], but may eas-\n105\tily degrade perceptual quality. More recently, neural audio\n106\tcodecs have been explored as purifiers, as their compres-\n107\tsion and decompression processes can remove adversarial\n108\tarXiv:2607.00899v1  [eess.AS]  1 Jul 2026\n109\t\n110\t\n111\t=== PAGE 2 ===\n112\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n113\t2\n114\t(a) Diffusion-based purification\n115\t(b) PnP\n116\t𝑥2\n117\t𝑥0\n118\t𝑥1\n119\t𝜋−noise\n120\tObservation:\n121\tForward noising \n122\tdominates robustness\n123\t……\n124\tForward (Noising)\n125\tReverse (Denoising)\n126\t𝑥2\n127\t𝑥0\n128\t𝑥1\n129\t𝑥𝑇\n130\tPurification path\n131\tFig. 1. From diffusion-based purification to PnP. Diffusion models for generative tasks perform a full forward process from x0 to xT , followed by reverse\n132\tsampling back to x0. In contrast, diffusion-based purification only relies on a partial forward and reverse process (an example of x0 →x2 →x0 is highlighted\n133\tin green). Motivated by the observation that most robustness gains actually come from the forward process, PnP reformulates purification as a learned forward\n134\tnoising procedure with task-beneficial positive-incentive noise (π-noise). The right part shows the diffusion-style PnP variant.\n135\tperturbations [24]. Generative approaches have also shown\n136\tstrong performance. Diffusion-based adversarial purification\n137\t(DAP) [25] was the first to introduce diffusion models for\n138\tASV purification, and textual-driven adversarial purification\n139\t(TDAP) [26] further adds text conditioning into the purifi-\n140\tcation process. Despite their strong defense performance,\n141\tdiffusion-based purification methods typically require step-\n142\tby-step sampling, which leads to high latency. Two-stage\n143\tdiffusion-based purification (TDP) [27] improves efficiency by\n144\tpurifying in a Mel-spectrogram latent space, but still relies on\n145\ta vocoder to reconstruct waveforms, which degrades audio\n146\tquality. Compared with proactive and detection-based passive\n147\tdefenses, purification is more attractive in few-shot or zero-\n148\tshot settings since it does not require model modification or\n149\tthreshold calibration.\n150\tA diffusion-based purifier consists of two stages. The for-\n151\tward noising process gradually corrupts the input toward pure\n152\tGaussian noise, and the reverse denoising process iteratively\n153\tpredicts and removes the injected noise. From this viewpoint,\n154\tthe forward noising process alone is conceptually close to\n155\tadditive-noise defense methods [23], which also perturb the\n156\tinput with noise of fixed standard deviation. This observation\n157\tnaturally raises a question: is the reverse denoising process\n158\tnecessary for effective adversarial purification?\n159\tIf most robustness gains already come from forward noising,\n160\tadversarial purification for ASV can instead be reformulated as\n161\ta learned forward noising problem, rather than relying on a full\n162\tdiffusion-based purification pipeline. Our preliminary experi-\n163\tments support this hypothesis. Motivated by this observation,\n164\twe propose a unified input-adaptive Positive-Incentive Noise\n165\tPredictor (PnP) framework, which learns task-beneficial noise\n166\tas a front-end purification module for speaker verification.\n167\tFig. 1 illustrates this shift in perspective. Instead of relying\n168\ton reverse denoising, we focus on the forward process and\n169\tinvestigate whether the injected noise can be learned to be\n170\ttask-beneficial. Under this framework, PnP-Gaussian pro-\n171\tvides a simple additive formulation, while PnP-Diff provides\n172\ta diffusion-style formulation aligned with the forward noising\n173\tprocess of a diffusion model. Moreover, the diffusion-style\n174\tvariant can be optionally cascaded with a diffusion denoiser\n175\tfor audio quality enhancement.\n176\tThe main contributions are summarized below.\n177\t• We revisit diffusion-based audio adversarial purification\n178\tand show that robustness gains come largely from the\n179\tforward noising process rather than the more expensive\n180\treverse denoising process. This provides a new perspec-\n181\ttive for simplifying diffusion-based defenses in ASV.\n182\t• Based on this observation, we propose the first frame-\n183\twork that uses positive-incentive noise (π-noise) in the\n184\tadversarial purification task. Our PnP method learns\n185\tinput-adaptive π-noise as a front-end purifier for ASV.\n186\tWithin this unified framework, PnP-Gaussian serves as\n187\tan adaptive version of additive noising, while PnP-Diff\n188\treplaces the fixed Gaussian forward noise in diffusion\n189\tpurification with learned π-noise.\n190\t• Extensive experiments show that the proposed framework\n191\tconsistently improves adversarial robustness in ASV un-\n192\tder white-box, black-box, and defender-aware adaptive\n193\tattacks. The 1-step and 2-step PnP-Diff variants achieve\n194\tstate-of-the-art robustness across different attack settings\n195\twith a real-time factor (RTF) of 0.014. In addition,\n196\tcascading PnP-Diff with a diffusion denoiser further im-\n197\tproves perceptual quality, reaching a WB-PESQ of 3.591\n198\tand an SI-SDR of 21.14 dB on adversarial VoxCeleb data.\n199\tII. BACKGROUND\n200\tA. Automatic Speaker Verification\n201\tAn ASV system aims to verify the speaker identity of\n202\tan input test utterance xtest. Given a pair of waveforms\n203\t(xtest, xenroll), where xenroll is an enrollment utterance from a\n204\tknown speaker, the ASV system extracts speaker embeddings\n205\tand computes a similarity score s(xtest, xenroll) between them.\n206\tThe verification decision is made by comparing the similarity\n207\tscore with a threshold.\n208\tCommon ASV embedding extractors include x-vector [28],\n209\tECAPA-TDNN [29], and ResNet-based encoders [30]. These\n210\tsystems typically take logarithmic filterbanks (LogFBank) as\n211\tinput. Recently, self-supervised learning (SSL) speech models\n212\tsuch as wav2vec 2.0 [2] and WavLM [3] have also been\n213\tadopted as upstream feature extractors, replacing conventional\n214\tLogFBank features [31].\n215\tB. Adversarial attacks in ASV\n216\tAdversarial attacks were first introduced in the image clas-\n217\tsification domain [6]. Despite appearing visually similar to\n218\toriginal genuine examples, adversarial images can mislead\n219\twell-trained classifiers. Such examples are typically crafted\n220\t\n221\t\n222\t=== PAGE 3 ===\n223\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n224\t3\n225\tto cross the classification boundary while being constrained\n226\tby an ℓp norm to remain imperceptible. Subsequent works\n227\tproposed stronger optimization-based attacks and robustness\n228\tevaluations, such as FGSM [8], PGD [10], and CW [32]. These\n229\tattacks can be conducted in a white-box setting, where the\n230\tattacker has full model knowledge, or in a black-box setting,\n231\twhere the attacker has no access to the internal parameters of\n232\tthe target model and may then rely on either transfer-based or\n233\tquery-based methods.\n234\tIn the ASV setting, the attacker aims to craft a perturbed\n235\tadversarial test utterance xadv = xtest + δ with extremely\n236\tsmall ∥δ∥p. Although xadv still sounds identical to xtest, it\n237\tmay cause false accepts for unauthorized speakers or false\n238\trejects for genuine speakers.\n239\tIn this paper, we consider MI-FGSM [33] and PGD [10] as\n240\ttwo strong, gradient-based attacks.\n241\t1) MI-FGSM:\n242\tMomentum iterative fast gradient sign\n243\tmethod (MI-FGSM) is an iterative ℓ∞attack with momentum.\n244\tLet J (x) denote the attack objective. Starting from x0 = xtest\n245\tand g0 = 0, MI-FGSM iterates\n246\tgk+1 = µ gk +\n247\t∇xJ (xk)\n248\t∥∇xJ (xk)∥1\n249\t,\n250\t(1)\n251\txk+1 = ΠB∞(xk + α · sign(gk+1)) ,\n252\t(2)\n253\twhere α is the step size, µ is the momentum decay, and ΠBp(·)\n254\tdenotes the projection onto a norm sphere ℓp that constrains\n255\tthe perturbation magnitude.\n256\t2) PGD: Projected gradient descent (PGD) is a multi-step\n257\tfirst-order attack with projection. Let J (x) denote the attack\n258\tobjective. In our experiments, we evaluate PGD-ℓ∞and PGD-\n259\tℓ2 attacks under different types of norm constraints. Starting\n260\tfrom x0 = xtest, PGD iterates\n261\tPGD-ℓ∞:\n262\txk+1 = ΠB∞(xk + α · sign(∇xJ (xk))) , (3)\n263\tPGD-ℓ2 :\n264\txk+1 = ΠB2\n265\t\u0012\n266\txk + α ·\n267\t∇xJ (xk)\n268\t∥∇xJ (xk)∥2\n269\t\u0013\n270\t.\n271\t(4)\n272\tC. Diffusion-based purification\n273\tTo protect models from adversarial attacks, purification\n274\tmethods aim to remove adversarial perturbations from the\n275\tinput. DiffPure [34] was first proposed to defend image\n276\tclassifiers with pretrained diffusion models. As a diffusion\n277\tmodel consists of a forward noising process and a reverse\n278\tdenoising process, given an input sample x0, the forward\n279\tprocess can be formulated as\n280\txt = √¯αt x0 +\n281\t√\n282\t1 −¯αt ϵ,\n283\t(5)\n284\twhere ϵ ∼N(0, I) is a Gaussian noise and ¯αt at step t\n285\tis computed by a predefined noise schedule. In the reverse\n286\tprocess, the diffusion model is trained to predict an esti-\n287\tmated noise ϵθ to remove this noise step by step. Given\n288\tan adversarial input xadv and a chosen purification step t∗,\n289\tDiffPure applies the forward process to obtain xadv\n290\tt∗\n291\tbefore\n292\tthe reverse process. AudioPure [35] subsequently applies this\n293\tidea to adversarial audio for speech emotion classification. In\n294\tthe ASV domain, unlike DiffPure and AudioPure, DAP [25]\n295\tis trained on adversarial data and runs the full reverse process\n296\t1\n297\t2\n298\t3\n299\tForward diffusion step t *\n300\t4.0\n301\t4.5\n302\t5.0\n303\t5.5\n304\t6.0\n305\t6.5\n306\t7.0\n307\tPurified Adv. EER (%)\n308\tAudioPure (Forward + reverse)\n309\tAudioPure (Forward stage only)\n310\tFig. 2.\n311\tMethod motivation from diffusion purification analysis. In this\n312\tpreliminary experiment, we compare the purified adversarial EERs of two\n313\tAudioPure-based purifiers under 50-step MI-FGSM attack, including the\n314\tfull AudioPure purifier with forward noising plus reverse denoising and its\n315\tforward-stage-only purifier variant. The small gap between the two curves\n316\tindicates that forward noising already provides most of the robustness.\n317\tdirectly on xadv rather than xadv\n318\tt∗, which yields better audio\n319\tquality for purified utterances but requires extra inference\n320\ttime; additionally, DAP requires large-scale adversarial audio.\n321\tSample-specific noise injection (SSNI) [36] further replaces\n322\tthe shared purification level t∗with a sample-specific t(x)\n323\testimated from the score magnitude of a pretrained diffusion\n324\tmodel. SSNI is similar to our work in that it also questions the\n325\tuse of a fixed forward noising process. However, SSNI still\n326\tassumes Gaussian noise in the forward process and retains\n327\tthe reverse denoising procedure, whereas our PnP framework\n328\tlearns task-beneficial noise and makes the denoiser optional.\n329\tIII. POSITIVE-INCENTIVE NOISE PREDICTOR FOR ASV\n330\tADVERSARIAL PURIFICATION\n331\tThis section first motivates the Positive-Incentive Noise\n332\tPredictor (PnP) through a preliminary experiment in Sec-\n333\ttion III-A. Section III-B then introduces the unified PnP\n334\tframework and its learning objective. Section III-C presents\n335\tits applications to adversarial purification.\n336\tA. Motivation from Diffusion-Based Purification\n337\tAdversarial purification protects a downstream ASV model\n338\tfrom the influence of adversarial perturbations. By revisit-\n339\ting the diffusion-based purification pipeline through AudioP-\n340\ture [35], we investigate whether most robustness gains already\n341\tarise from the forward noising stage. In particular, we compare\n342\tthe defense performance of the full AudioPure pipeline with\n343\tits forward-process-only variant on VoxCeleb1 data attacked\n344\tby MI-FGSM. As shown in Fig. 2, the forward-only variant\n345\tachieves purified adversarial EERs that are very close to those\n346\tof the full pipeline across different forward diffusion steps.\n347\tMore detailed stepwise analysis of AudioPure is provided\n348\tin Section V-B. This motivates us to learn a task-beneficial\n349\tforward noising process, which we formulate next through a\n350\tpositive-incentive learning objective.\n351\t\n352\t\n353\t=== PAGE 4 ===\n354\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n355\t4\n356\tASV\n357\t(Frozen)\n358\tGenuine Consistency\n359\tAlign ො𝑥gen with 𝑥gen\n360\tAdversarial Recovery\n361\tAlign ො𝑥adv with 𝑥gen\n362\tPositive-Incentive Objective (ℒrobust)\n363\t𝑥gen\n364\t𝑥adv\n365\tො𝑥gen\n366\tො𝑥adv\n367\t+𝛿\n368\tPnP\n369\tFig. 3. Training pipeline of the proposed positive-incentive noise predictor (PnP). For each input genuine utterance xgen, we generate its adversarial example\n370\txadv = xgen + δ. PnP processes the genuine and adversarial inputs, and produces purified outputs ˆxgen and ˆxadv, which are then fed into a frozen ASV\n371\tsystem. The PnP parameters are optimized to increase speaker similarity between the genuine reference and the purified outputs from both branches, thereby\n372\tpreserving performance on unattacked inputs while suppressing adversarial perturbations.\n373\tB. Unified PnP Framework\n374\tWe now introduce the unified waveform-level framework\n375\tfor ASV adversarial purification and its learning objective.\n376\tPrevious additive-noise defenses [23] and diffusion-based\n377\tpurification methods [35] commonly rely on task-agnostic\n378\trandom noising. In contrast, PnP replaces this random noising\n379\twith a learnable positive-incentive noising process.\n380\t1) Framework: Fig. 3 illustrates the implementation of the\n381\tASV-guided PnP framework. Given an input waveform x, PnP\n382\tpredicts input-adaptive positive-incentive noise (π-noise) and\n383\tcombines it with the input to construct a purified waveform ˆx\n384\tfor downstream ASV scoring. Unlike ordinary random noise,\n385\tπ-noise benefits a target task, as it is expected to reduce the\n386\tuncertainty of the downstream task rather than simply corrupt\n387\tthe input [37]. In our ASV purification setting, this means\n388\tthat the learned noise should encourage the purified waveform\n389\tto preserve speaker information while suppressing adversarial\n390\tperturbations.\n391\tSpecifically, we construct a learnable noise predictor εω by\n392\tcombining a normalized directional component predicted by a\n393\t1-D U-Net ˜ε with Gaussian noise:\n394\tεω(x) = λ\n395\t˜ε(x)\n396\t∥˜ε(x)∥2\n397\t+\n398\tp\n399\t1 −λ2 ϵ,\n400\t(6)\n401\twhere ϵ ∼N(0, I) and λ ∈[0, 1] controls the mixture ratio.\n402\tTo incorporate the predicted π-noise into the input wave-\n403\tform for purification, we adopt a unified weighted mixing\n404\tformulation:\n405\tˆx = wx x + wn εω(x),\n406\t(7)\n407\twhere ˆx denotes the purified waveform, and wx and wn control\n408\tthe contributions of the original signal x and the predicted\n409\tnoise εω(x), respectively. Different choices of wx and wn\n410\tlead to different PnP variants, as introduced in Section III-C.\n411\tThe complete procedures are summarized in three algorithms.\n412\tAlgorithm 1 trains the π-noise predictor guided by a frozen\n413\tASV system. Algorithm 2 deploys the trained predictor as\n414\ta lightweight pre-processing module. Algorithm 3 further\n415\tdescribes how to train a diffusion denoiser with PnP-generated\n416\tπ-noise for the optional cascade.\n417\t2) Positive-Incentive Learning Objective: We next formal-\n418\tize the positive-incentive learning objective used to train PnP.\n419\tIn the original formulation, π-noise is defined as a noise vari-\n420\table that reduces the uncertainty of the downstream task. For\n421\ta task T , this means that after introducing a π-noise variable\n422\tε, the task becomes more predictable, i.e., H(T | ε) < H(T ),\n423\twhere H(·) denotes information entropy. If ε does not change\n424\tthe task uncertainty, i.e., H(T\n425\t| ε) = H(T ), then it can\n426\tbe regarded as pure noise. The variational positive-incentive\n427\tnoise (VPN) formulation [38] further shows that this positive-\n428\tincentive objective can be optimized through a variational\n429\tlower bound.\n430\tIn ASV adversarial purification, this perspective is applied\n431\tthrough two directions. The learned noise in PnP should guide\n432\tboth genuine and adversarial inputs in a way that benefits\n433\tdownstream ASV decisions better than random noise. For gen-\n434\tuine inputs, PnP should preserve the verification performance\n435\tof a well-trained ASV system. For adversarial inputs, PnP\n436\tshould suppress adversarial perturbations so that the purified\n437\tadversarial input moves back toward the genuine reference in\n438\tthe speaker embedding space.\n439\tWe instantiate the positive-incentive formulation in the ASV\n440\tsetting as follows. Let T denote the speaker verification task,\n441\tx denote an input utterance, and y ∈[−1, 1] denote the ASV\n442\tverification score. We represent the task by the continuous\n443\tscore y with density p(y | x), and define the task entropy as\n444\tH(T | x) = Ex\n445\th\n446\t−\n447\tZ\n448\tp(y | x) log p(y | x) dy\n449\ti\n450\t.\n451\t(8)\n452\tLet ε be a noise variable sampled from the distribution\n453\tDω(x, y) parameterized by ω. By definition, the mutual in-\n454\tformation between T and ε is\n455\tI(T , ε | x) = Ex Eε\n456\th Z\n457\tp(y, ε | x) log\n458\tp(y, ε | x)\n459\tp(y | x) p(ε | x) dy\n460\ti\n461\t.\n462\t(9)\n463\tTherefore, if I(T , ε | x) > 0, the noise variable ε\n464\tbecomes positive-incentive noise for task T . Following the\n465\tVPN formulation [38], we optimize a variational lower bound\n466\tof I(T , ε | x). For ASV adversarial purification, we consider\n467\tpaired genuine and adversarial inputs in each mini-batch,\n468\t\n469\t\n470\t=== PAGE 5 ===\n471\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n472\t5\n473\tdenoted by {(xgen\n474\ti\n475\t, xadv\n476\ti\n477\t)}B\n478\ti=1, and expand the variational\n479\tlower bound over the two branches as\n480\tLπ ≈1\n481\tB\n482\tB\n483\tX\n484\ti=1\n485\tEε\n486\t\u0002\n487\tlog q(yi | xgen\n488\ti\n489\t, ε)\n490\t\u0003\n491\t+ 1\n492\tB\n493\tB\n494\tX\n495\ti=1\n496\tEε\n497\t\u0002\n498\tlog q(yi | xadv\n499\ti\n500\t, ε)\n501\t\u0003\n502\t,\n503\t(10)\n504\twhere q(y | x, ε) is a variational approximation to p(y | x, ε),\n505\tand we assume that Dω(x, y) is Gaussian. Since xadv\n506\ti\n507\tis\n508\tderived from xgen\n509\ti\n510\t, in practice we parameterize the noise\n511\tgenerator using the genuine and adversarial inputs, i.e.,\n512\tDω(xgen, xadv), rather than explicitly relying on the value of\n513\ty.\n514\tThe two terms in Lπ correspond to the two desired effects\n515\tof PnP, preserving ASV performance for genuine inputs and\n516\tsuppressing adversarial perturbations for adversarial inputs.\n517\tIdeally, the π-noise predictor εω should maximize these two\n518\tvariational terms. However, directly estimating the variational\n519\tdensity q(y | x, ε) is difficult in ASV, since the output\n520\tis a verification score rather than an explicit probabilistic\n521\tdistribution. We therefore use ASV scores as a task-driven\n522\tsurrogate for the positive-incentive objective. Specifically, we\n523\tmaximize the similarity between the genuine reference and\n524\tboth purified genuine and adversarial outputs. A hinge margin\n525\tprevents unnecessary optimization once the similarity score is\n526\tsufficiently high. Other surrogate formulations could also be\n527\tused to optimize the same objective.\n528\tAs shown in Fig. 3, during PnP training, we first generate\n529\txadv for a given xgen, and then compute ˆxgen and ˆxadv with\n530\tEq. (7). We enforce high speaker similarity between the clean\n531\treference xgen and the two purified outputs, ˆxgen and ˆxadv,\n532\tby minimizing the high-margin hinge loss:\n533\tLrobust = ϕm\n534\t\u0000s(xgen, ˆxgen)\n535\t\u0001\n536\t+ ϕm\n537\t\u0000s(xgen, ˆxadv)\n538\t\u0001\n539\t,\n540\t(11)\n541\twhere ϕm(s) = max(0, m −s) with m chosen close to 1.\n542\tTo regularize the magnitude of the learned π-noise, we\n543\tpenalize the energy:\n544\tLreg = ∥εω(xgen)∥2\n545\t2 +\n546\t\r\rεω(xadv)\n547\t\r\r2\n548\t2 .\n549\t(12)\n550\tThe overall training loss is then given by:\n551\tL(ω) = Lrobust + γLreg,\n552\t(13)\n553\twhere γ > 0 is a weighting coefficient. Algorithm 1 summa-\n554\trizes the training procedure.\n555\tDuring the test stage, we deploy the trained PnP as a pre-\n556\tprocessing purification module in front of an ASV system.\n557\tGiven a test utterance x, PnP predicts task-beneficial noise\n558\tand mixes it with the input according to Eq. (6) and Eq. (7)\n559\tto suppress potential adversarial perturbations. Algorithm 2\n560\tsummarizes the inference procedure.\n561\tC. Applications to Adversarial Purification\n562\tBased on the unified mixing formulation in Eq. (7), PnP\n563\tcan be instantiated by choosing different weights for the input\n564\twaveform and the predicted π-noise. We consider two basic\n565\tstandalone variants for ASV adversarial purification, namely\n566\tAlgorithm 1 Train a positive-incentive noise predictor with a\n567\tfrozen ASV system\n568\tInput: Training set {(xgen\n569\ti , xadv\n570\ti )}n\n571\ti=1, batch size B, and a\n572\tfrozen ASV system.\n573\tOutput: Trained π-noise predictor εω.\n574\t1: Initialize εω.\n575\t2: for each sampled mini-batch {(xgen\n576\ti , xadv\n577\ti )}B\n578\ti=1 do\n579\t3:\n580\tfor each (xgen\n581\ti , xadv\n582\ti ) do\n583\t4:\n584\tGenerate\n585\tπ-noise\n586\tεω(xgen\n587\ti\n588\t)\n589\tand\n590\tεω(xadv\n591\ti\n592\t)\n593\twith\n594\tEq. (6).\n595\t5:\n596\tObtain purified utterances ˆxgen\n597\ti\n598\tand ˆxadv\n599\ti\n600\twith Eq. (7).\n601\t6:\n602\tend for\n603\t7:\n604\tCompute Lrobust with the frozen ASV system with\n605\tEq. (11), and compute Lreg with Eq. (12).\n606\t8:\n607\tUpdate εω by minimizing L(ω) = Lrobust + γLreg.\n608\t9: end for\n609\tAlgorithm 2 Purify a test sample with a trained positive-\n610\tincentive noise predictor.\n611\tInput: Trained π-noise predictor εω and test sample x.\n612\tOutput: Purified sample ˆx.\n613\t1: Predict the π-noise εω(x) according to Eq. (6).\n614\t2: Compute the purified sample ˆx by Eq. (7).\n615\t3: Return ˆx for downstream ASV scoring.\n616\tPnP-Gaussian and PnP-Diff. In addition, PnP-Diff can be\n617\toptionally cascaded with a diffusion denoiser as an extension\n618\tfor further processing.\n619\t1) PnP-Gaussian: When wx = wn = 1, PnP reduces to\n620\tsimply adding the learned noise to the original input:\n621\tˆx = x + εω(x).\n622\t(14)\n623\tWe refer to this simplest variant as PnP-Gaussian.\n624\t2) PnP-Diff: In vanilla diffusion models, the forward pro-\n625\tcess is a Markov chain that gradually corrupts the input\n626\tby combining the clean signal and Gaussian noise with\n627\tcoefficients determined by a noise schedule. Motivated by\n628\tthis formulation, we define a diffusion-style variant, PnP-\n629\tDiff, which aligns PnP with the diffusion forward process.\n630\tSpecifically, we set the weights wx and wn according to the\n631\tstandard cumulative diffusion noise schedule {¯αt}, where √¯αt\n632\tand √1 −¯αt weight the signal and noise terms, respectively.\n633\tThe PnP-Diff output at timestep t is then given by\n634\tˆx = √¯αt x +\n635\t√\n636\t1 −¯αt εω(x, t).\n637\t(15)\n638\tCompared with PnP-Gaussian, PnP-Diff explicitly follows\n639\tthe diffusion noise schedule and can therefore be combined\n640\tnaturally with a diffusion reverse process starting from ˆx.\n641\t3) Optional diffusion denoiser cascade: PnP-Diff supports\n642\tan optional extension in which its forward output is further\n643\tprocessed by a diffusion denoiser. This denoiser can be either\n644\ta pretrained model or a model retrained with PnP-generated\n645\tπ-noise.\n646\tFor this cascade, we treat the PnP-Diff output as a diffusion-\n647\tstyle corrupted sample, since it follows the same noise sched-\n648\tule as the standard diffusion forward process. In this case,\n649\t\n650\t\n651\t=== PAGE 6 ===\n652\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n653\t6\n654\tAlgorithm 3 Train a diffusion model with PnP-generated π-\n655\tnoise\n656\tInput: Trained PnP-Diff generator εω, training utterances\n657\t{xi}n\n658\ti=1, batch size B, maximum diffusion timestep T.\n659\tOutput: Diffusion model ϵθ.\n660\t1: Initialize ϵθ.\n661\t2: for each sampled mini-batch {xi}B\n662\ti=1 do\n663\t3:\n664\tSample timesteps ti ∼Uniform{1, . . . , T} for i =\n665\t1, . . . , B.\n666\t4:\n667\tfor each xi in the mini-batch do\n668\t5:\n669\tGenerate π-noise εi = εω(xi, ti).\n670\t6:\n671\tForm the corrupted sample xt,i from xi and εi\n672\taccording to Eq. (15).\n673\t7:\n674\tend for\n675\t8:\n676\tCompute the diffusion loss 1\n677\tB\n678\tPB\n679\ti=1\n680\t\r\rεi−ϵθ(xt,i, ti)\n681\t\r\r2\n682\t2.\n683\t9:\n684\tUpdate θ by minimizing the diffusion loss.\n685\t10: end for\n686\tas shown in Algorithm 3, we use xt rather than ˆx to denote\n687\tthe mixture of x and εω(x, t), so that it aligns better with\n688\tthe diffusion model. Specifically, PnP-Diff replaces Gaussian\n689\tnoise in the diffusion forward process with learned π-noise\n690\tεω(x, t), and constructs xt according to Eq. (15). This allows\n691\ta diffusion reverse process to be applied after the PnP-Diff\n692\tforward step for further quality enhancement.\n693\tOn top of this PnP-driven forward process, we can then\n694\tretrain a diffusion denoiser ϵθ(xt, t) to predict the injected\n695\tπ-noise. The diffusion model loss is formulated as\n696\tLdiff = Ex, t Eεω(x,t)\n697\th\r\rεω(x, t) −ϵθ(xt, t)\n698\t\r\r2\n699\t2\n700\ti\n701\t.\n702\t(16)\n703\tThis loss function encourages the reverse process to remove\n704\tthe PnP-generated π-noise. Algorithm 3 summarizes the cor-\n705\tresponding training procedure.\n706\tIV. EXPERIMENTAL SETTINGS\n707\tA. Datasets\n708\tWe conduct most of experiments on the VoxCeleb bench-\n709\tmarks [39], [40]. VoxCeleb1 and VoxCeleb2 dataset are\n710\textracted from YouTube videos and include thousands of\n711\tspeakers. To train the ASV backbones, we follow common\n712\tprotocol and use the full VoxCeleb2 dataset, except pretrained\n713\tSimAMResNet using VoxBlink2 [41]. The VoxCeleb1 devel-\n714\topment subset of is used to train the proposed PnP methods\n715\twith VoxCeleb1-E trial list.\n716\tWe evaluate adversarial attack and defense performance\n717\tover 4,000 paired verification trials from VoxCeleb1 test\n718\tset. To balance computational cost and generalizability, we\n719\tconstruct this subset by randomly sampling 50 non-target\n720\ttrials and 50 target trials for each enrollment speaker from\n721\tthe VoxCeleb1-O trial list. In addition, because there are\n722\tno transcriptions for VoxCeleb dataset, 1,000 utterances are\n723\trandomly selected from the LibriSpeech train-clean-100 subset\n724\t[42] and used for word error rate (WER) evaluation.\n725\tB. ASV systems\n726\tWe conduct adversarial attack and defense experiments on\n727\tfour widely used state-of-the-art ASV backbones: ECAPA-\n728\tTDNN [29], CAM++ [43], ResNet [30], and SimAMRes-\n729\tNet [44]. All models are implemented using the WeSpeaker\n730\ttoolkit [45] and take 80-dimensional LogFBank coefficients as\n731\tinput features.\n732\tECAPA-TDNN and CAM++ are lightweight embedding\n733\textractors that produce 512-dimensional speaker embeddings,\n734\twith 6.4M and 7.2M parameters, respectively. In contrast,\n735\tResNet and SimAMResNet provide higher-capacity back-\n736\tbones. ResNet has 221 layers and outputs 256-dimensional\n737\tembeddings with 23.8M parameters, while SimAMResNet has\n738\t100 layers, also outputs 256-dimensional embeddings, and\n739\tcontains 50.2M parameters.\n740\tC. Adversarial attacks\n741\tFor white-box attacks, we evaluate three strong gradient-\n742\tbased waveform-domain attacks: MI-FGSM [33], PGD-ℓ∞,\n743\tand PGD-ℓ2 [10]. For MI-FGSM and PGD-ℓ∞, we set the\n744\tstep size to α = 1, the ℓ∞perturbation budget to 30, and the\n745\tmomentum decay in MI-FGSM to µ = 1. For PGD-ℓ2, we\n746\tset the step size to α = 500 and the perturbation budget to\n747\t6400. All white-box attacks are targeted and implemented with\n748\tthe torchattacks1 toolkit. In addition, all white-box attacks are\n749\talso evaluated under a defender-aware adaptive attack setting,\n750\twhere the attacker also has access to the architecture and\n751\tparameters of purification methods.\n752\tFor black-box attacks, we consider FAKEBOB [13], a\n753\tquery-based targeted false-accept attack for ASV. We set the\n754\tperturbation budget to ϵF B = 160, and the maximum number\n755\tof iterations to 150. Our implementation follows the public\n756\tFAKEBOB2 repository.\n757\tAll attacks are targeted because they correspond to ASV\n758\timpersonation scenarios, where an attacker attempts to be\n759\taccepted as a target speaker and gain unauthorized access.\n760\tD. Purification methods\n761\tWe compare the proposed PnP with several representative\n762\tpurification baselines. DAP [25] is a diffusion-based adversar-\n763\tial purification method for ASV that adopts a DiffWave [46]\n764\tbackbone conditioned on Mel-spectrograms; we train it under\n765\tthe same adversarial data and setting as PnP-Diff for a fair\n766\tcomparison. AudioPure uses a diffusion model pretrained\n767\ton genuine data; we use the official checkpoint3 for test-\n768\ting. We additionally implement AudioPure-SSNI following\n769\tSSNI [36]. We retain the pretrained AudioPure backbone\n770\tand replace the fixed purification step with a sample-specific\n771\tstep determined from the predicted-noise trajectory. We also\n772\tinclude simple additive Gaussian-noise baselines [23], denoted\n773\tas Noise-σ, where zero-mean Gaussian noise with standard\n774\tdeviation σ ∈{0.005, 0.01, 0.02} is directly added to the\n775\twaveform. For neural codec-based purifiers [24], the input\n776\t1https://github.com/Harry24k/adversarial-attacks-pytorch\n777\t2https://github.com/FAKEBOB-adversarial-attack/FAKEBOB\n778\t3https://github.com/cychomatica/AudioPure\n779\t\n780\t\n781\t=== PAGE 7 ===\n782\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n783\t7\n784\twaveform is compressed into a latent representation and then\n785\tdecompressed. We evaluate three pretrained codecs at 16 kHz:\n786\tSpeechTokenizer4 [47], DAC5 [48], and AcademiCodec (HiFi-\n787\tCodec-16k-320d-large-universal)6 [49].\n788\tFor PnP, we instantiate an unconditional 1-D U-Net Dif-\n789\tfWave [46] as the noise predictor and consider two variants,\n790\tPnP-Gaussian and PnP-Diff. PnP-Gaussian directly adds the\n791\tpredicted noise to the input, whereas PnP-Diff follows the\n792\tdiffusion-style forward corruption defined in Eq. (15). For both\n793\tvariants, the mixture coefficient in Eq. (6) is fixed to λ = 0.7.\n794\tFor PnP-Diff, we use a 50-step linear noise schedule with\n795\tβt linearly increasing from 10−4 to 0.05. During training,\n796\tPnP-Diff samples timesteps uniformly from t ∈{1, 2, 3},\n797\twhile PnP-Gaussian is timestep-free. At inference time, we\n798\tuse t∗= 1 as the default purification step for all PnP-Diff- and\n799\tAudioPure-based methods, since a smaller timestep introduces\n800\tmilder degradation to the input. Other timestep settings are\n801\tindicated in the method name, e.g., PnP-Diff-2 denotes t∗= 2.\n802\tPnP-Diff is trained on 50-step PGD-ℓ2 adversarial examples\n803\tgenerated against ECAPA-TDNN using the VoxCeleb1 devel-\n804\topment data and the VoxCeleb1-E trial list, with the margin\n805\tin Eq. (11) set to m = 0.9. PnP-Gaussian is trained on the\n806\t20-step ECAPA PGD-ℓ2 adversarial set from the same trials\n807\twith margin m = 1.0.\n808\tIn addition, PnP-Diff can be cascaded with a diffusion\n809\tdenoiser to further improve perceptual quality. In this setting,\n810\tPnP-Diff serves as a replacement for the standard forward\n811\tnoising process. We evaluate two options, PnP-Diff + AudioP-\n812\ture, which cascades PnP-Diff with a pretrained AudioPure de-\n813\tnoiser, and PnP-Diff + DiffWavePnP, which uses a DiffWave\n814\tdenoiser trained with π-noise generated from PnP-Diff on the\n815\tsame 50-step PGD-ℓ2 VoxCeleb1 development data.\n816\tE. Evaluation Metrics\n817\tWe report three groups of metrics covering ASV defense\n818\tperformance, audio quality and intelligibility, and inference\n819\tspeed.\n820\tFor ASV defense performance and detection, we measure\n821\tthe equal error rate (EER) of the ASV system before and\n822\tafter purification, reported separately on genuine (noattacked)\n823\tinputs and adversarial data for each trial. We also evaluate\n824\tadversarial example detection by thresholding the ASV score\n825\tshift induced by purification and report the corresponding\n826\tdetection rate when distinguishing adversarial from genuine\n827\tinputs.\n828\tFor audio quality and intelligibility, we report objective\n829\tmetrics, including wideband perceptual evaluation of speech\n830\tquality (WB-PESQ), scale-invariant signal-to-distortion ratio\n831\t(SI-SDR), short-time objective intelligibility (STOI), MOS\n832\tprediction from a finetuned self-supervised model (MOS-\n833\tSSL) [50], and WER. WB-PESQ, SI-SDR, and STOI are\n834\tcomputed using the torchmetrics7 toolkit. For MOS-SSL, we\n835\tuse a finetuned wav2vec 2.0 small model as the SSL predictor.\n836\t4https://huggingface.co/OpenMOSS-Team/SpeechTokenizer\n837\t5https://github.com/descriptinc/descript-audio-codec\n838\t6https://github.com/yangdongchao/AcademiCodec\n839\t7https://github.com/Lightning-AI/torchmetrics\n840\tWER is evaluated with a Whisper8 model. For inference speed,\n841\twe report the real-time factor (RTF) of each method, defined\n842\tas the ratio between model processing time and input duration.\n843\tASV processing time is also included.\n844\tV. EXPERIMENTAL RESULTS\n845\tWe first show the effect of adversarial attacks on the victim\n846\tASV systems and then organize the discussion around three\n847\tquestions: (Q1) Is the reverse process really necessary in\n848\tdiffusion-based purification? (Q2) How effective is the pro-\n849\tposed PnP method against black-box, white-box and adaptive\n850\tadversarial attackers? (Q3) How can PnP be cascaded with dif-\n851\tfusion models to further improve the quality and intelligibility\n852\tfor purified utterances?\n853\tA. Attack performance without purification\n854\tBefore evaluating purification, we first verify that the attack\n855\tsettings are sufficiently strong for unprotected ASV systems.\n856\tFor white-box attacks, we consider MI-FGSM, PGD-ℓ2, and\n857\tPGD-ℓ∞as three targeted methods. For each ASV backend\n858\tand each attack, we fix the perturbation budget and vary the\n859\titeration number K ∈{5, 10, 20, 50, 100, 200} to control the\n860\tattack strength. For genuine inputs, ECAPA-TDNN, CAM++,\n861\tResNet, and SimAMResNet achieve EERs of 1.25%, 0.85%,\n862\t0.70%, and 0.20%, respectively, indicating that the backbones\n863\tthemselves are reliable before adversarial attack.\n864\tAs shown in Fig. 4, increasing K rapidly raises the EER\n865\tfor all three white-box attacks across all four ASV backbones.\n866\tWhen the iteration number reaches 200, EERs are already in\n867\tthe order of 80% in most cases. At the same time, results in the\n868\tbottom row show that perturbations remain, with the average\n869\tSNR between unattacked and attacked waveforms consistently\n870\tabove 30 dB.\n871\tFor the black-box FAKEBOB attack, we report attack\n872\tsuccess rate (ASR) rather than EER as this is a query-based\n873\tfalse-accept attack. Without purification, FAKEBOB reaches\n874\t76.60% ASR on the test subset, while the generated adversarial\n875\tutterances have an average SNR of 24.95 dB. Overall, these\n876\tresults confirm that the unprotected ASV systems are highly\n877\tvulnerable under both white-box and black-box attacks. De-\n878\ttailed EER values and minDCF results are provided in the\n879\tsupplementary material.\n880\tB. Analysis of diffusion-based purification\n881\tTo better understand what drives diffusion-based purifica-\n882\ttion, we revisit AudioPure [35] as a representative baseline.\n883\tWe study AudioPure on ECAPA-TDNN under 50-step MI-\n884\tFGSM, where the unprotected system yields 1.25% EER on\n885\tgenuine trials and 69.35% EER on adversarial trials. AudioP-\n886\ture consists of a forward noising stage and a reverse denoising\n887\tstage. In the forward process, a waveform x is perturbed into\n888\txt = √¯αt x + √1 −¯αt ϵ, where ϵ is injected Gaussian noise\n889\tand ¯αt is the cumulative noise schedule.\n890\tWe compare three variants: (i) Full, which uses both forward\n891\tnoising and reverse denoising; (ii) Forward, which uses only\n892\t8https://huggingface.co/Systran/faster-whisper-large-v3\n893\t\n894\t\n895\t=== PAGE 8 ===\n896\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n897\t8\n898\t0\n899\t20\n900\t40\n901\t60\n902\t80\n903\tEER (%)\n904\tMI-FGSM\n905\tECAPA-TDNN\n906\tCAM++\n907\tResNet\n908\tSimAMResNet\n909\t0\n910\t20\n911\t40\n912\t60\n913\t80\n914\tPGD-L2\n915\t0\n916\t20\n917\t40\n918\t60\n919\t80\n920\tPGD-L∞\n921\t5\n922\t10\n923\t20\n924\t50\n925\t100\n926\t200\n927\tIterations\n928\t35\n929\t40\n930\t45\n931\t50\n932\tSNR (dB)\n933\t5\n934\t10\n935\t20\n936\t50\n937\t100\n938\t200\n939\tIterations\n940\t35\n941\t40\n942\t45\n943\t50\n944\t5\n945\t10\n946\t20\n947\t50\n948\t100\n949\t200\n950\tIterations\n951\t35\n952\t40\n953\t45\n954\t50\n955\tFig. 4. Attack strength on four unprotected ASV systems across attack iterations. The top row reports EER (%) on attacked test trials and the bottom row\n956\treports average SNR (dB) for adversarial perturbations. The three columns correspond to MI-FGSM, PGD-ℓ2, and PGD-ℓ∞, respectively, while different\n957\tcurves denote different ASV backbones.\n958\tTABLE I\n959\tANALYSIS OF THREE AUDIOPURE VARIANTS ON ECAPA-TDNN UNDER\n960\t50-STEP MI-FGSM ATTACK. “GEN” AND “ADV” DENOTE\n961\tPOST-PURIFICATION EERS ON GENUINE AND ADVERSARIAL TRIALS,\n962\tRESPECTIVELY. THE NO-PURIFICATION EERS ARE 1.25% FOR “GEN”\n963\tAND 69.35% FOR “ADV”. RTF IS MEASURED ON A 24-GB NVIDIA\n964\tGEFORCE RTX 3090 GPU.\n965\tAudioPure\n966\tt∗\n967\tFull\n968\tForward\n969\tForward without noise\n970\tGen\n971\tAdv\n972\tRTF\n973\tGen\n974\tAdv\n975\tRTF\n976\tGen\n977\tAdv\n978\tRTF\n979\t1\n980\t2.90\n981\t3.85\n982\t0.078\n983\t2.80\n984\t4.05\n985\t0.007\n986\t1.25\n987\t69.35\n988\t0.007\n989\t2\n990\t4.35\n991\t4.70\n992\t0.133\n993\t4.15\n994\t4.90\n995\t0.007\n996\t1.25\n997\t69.35\n998\t0.007\n999\t3\n1000\t6.40\n1001\t7.00\n1002\t0.212\n1003\t5.70\n1004\t5.95\n1005\t0.007\n1006\t1.25\n1007\t69.35\n1008\t0.007\n1009\tthe forward noising stage; and (iii) Forward without noise ,\n1010\twhich uses only xt = √¯αt x.\n1011\tTable I reports the EERs and RTFs of these variants for\n1012\tdifferent purification timesteps t∗. In terms of post-purification\n1013\tEERs on genuine and adversarial trials, forward-only Au-\n1014\tdioPure remains close to the full pipeline across all tested\n1015\tt∗, whereas its no-noise variant yields EERs similar to those\n1016\twithout purification. This answers Q1 and suggests that in-\n1017\tjected Gaussian noise in diffusion-based purification is the\n1018\tmain source of robustness. These observations motivate PnP,\n1019\twhich removes the costly reverse process and learns input-\n1020\tadaptive π-noise.\n1021\tC. Purification performance\n1022\tWe next use ECAPA-TDNN as a representative ASV back-\n1023\tbone to evaluate the end-to-end impact of purification. Results\n1024\tof PnP on other ASV systems are reported in Section V-G3.\n1025\tTable II illustrates the influence of purification on genuine\n1026\tunattacked inputs, white-box and black-box attacks, and in-\n1027\tference speed for all defenders. The ”No defender” row\n1028\treports EERs without purification and serves as the baseline\n1029\tto measure the reductions achieved by each purifier.\n1030\tFor genuine unattacked inputs, DAP has the lowest im-\n1031\tpact, but the proposed PnP-Diff variants introduce only a\n1032\tsmall degradation. Compared with the no-purification EER\n1033\tof 1.25%, DAP and PnP-Diff obtain 1.65% and 1.75%, re-\n1034\tspectively. In contrast, PnP-Gaussian reaches 4.30%, and the\n1035\tadditive-noise baselines are all above 2%, showing that the\n1036\tadditive formulation is more harmful on clean trials. This\n1037\tconfirms that the diffusion-style PnP design better preserves\n1038\tgenuine ASV performance.\n1039\tFor white-box attacks, adversarial examples are generated\n1040\tagainst ECAPA-TDNN and then evaluated on the same ASV\n1041\tafter purification. Among all methods, PnP-Diff provides the\n1042\tmost stable trade-off on genuine and attacked data. It maintains\n1043\tlow EERs for genuine utterances while achieving the strongest\n1044\tpooled white-box EERs across PGD-L2 and PGD-L∞. Here,\n1045\tPnP-Diff-2 denotes the two-step forward purification version\n1046\tof PnP-Diff. The two cascaded variants further show that the\n1047\tmain robustness gain already comes from the learned forward\n1048\tpurification.\n1049\tThe black-box FAKEBOB column tests whether this trend\n1050\ttransfers beyond gradient-based attacks. Since FAKEBOB\n1051\ttargets false accepts at a fixed verification threshold, we\n1052\treport attack success rate (ASR) rather than EER. PnP-Diff-\n1053\t2 and AcademiCodec achieve the best results, reducing the\n1054\tno-purification ASR from 76.60% to 2.40%. Overall, among\n1055\tall defenders, the 1-step PnP-Diff and its 2-step variant, PnP-\n1056\tDiff-2, provide the strongest performance under both white-\n1057\tbox and black-box attacks, and cause only limited degradation\n1058\ton genuine inputs.\n1059\tRTF evaluation further highlights PnP’s inference-speed\n1060\tadvantage. PnP-Gaussian, PnP-Diff, and PnP-Diff-2 all run\n1061\tat an RTF of 0.014, which is much faster than reverse-\n1062\tdiffusion pipelines such as AudioPure. The cascaded PnP-Diff\n1063\t\n1064\t\n1065\t=== PAGE 9 ===\n1066\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n1067\t9\n1068\tTABLE II\n1069\tIMPACT OF DIFFERENT PURIFICATION METHODS ON ECAPA-TDNN FOR GENUINE UNATTACKED INPUT, WHITE-BOX AND BLACK-BOX ATTACKS, AND\n1070\tINFERENCE SPEED. THE GENUINE COLUMN REPORTS EER (%) ON UNATTACKED TRIALS AFTER APPLYING EACH DEFENDER. THE WHITE-BOX COLUMNS\n1071\tREPORT EER (%) UNDER TARGETED MI-FGSM, PGD-ℓ2, AND PGD-ℓ∞ATTACKS, AND ‘POOLED’ DENOTES THE MEAN EER OVER ITERATIONS\n1072\t{10, 50, 200} FOR EACH ATTACKER. THE FAKEBOB COLUMN REPORTS BLACK-BOX ATTACK SUCCESS RATE. RTF MEASURES 