arial\n1347\trobustness under standard attacks, we next evaluate defender-\n1348\taware adaptive attacks and answer Q2. This experiment tests\n1349\tthe claim that PnP should remain useful even when the attacker\n1350\thas full knowledge of the purifier architecture and parameters.\n1351\tWe therefore assume that the attacker computes gradients\n1352\tthrough the whole defended ASV pipeline and evaluate the\n1353\tresulting EER under this adaptive attack setting.\n1354\tAs illustrated in Fig. 5, the attack objective is defined on\n1355\tthe defended pipeline ASV(Purifier(x)) rather than only on\n1356\tthe verifier ASV(x). To keep the comparison focused, from\n1357\tthis point we report only the best defender from each baseline\n1358\tfamily according to Table II.\n1359\tTable III focuses on 50-step MI-FGSM attacks and reports\n1360\tthe EER of adaptive examples when the attacked defender\n1361\tremains in the ASV pipeline, together with the EER of the\n1362\tsame examples after removing the defender. Among the PnP\n1363\tvariants, PnP-Diff-2 is the most stable under the matched\n1364\tadaptive evaluation. In contrast, PnP-Gaussian is much more\n1365\tvulnerable. However, after removing the defender, its adaptive\n1366\texamples no longer remain effective on the bare ASV again.\n1367\t𝑥gen\n1368\t𝑥adv = 𝑥gen + 𝛿\n1369\tupdate\n1370\tASV\n1371\tPurifier\n1372\tgradient backward\n1373\tFig. 5.\n1374\tAdaptive attack against the defended ASV pipeline. Black arrows\n1375\tdenote the defended forward inference from the clean input xgen through the\n1376\tpurifier and the ASV system. Red dashed arrows denote the backward gradient\n1377\tpath used by the attacker to update the adversarial input xadv = xgen + δ\n1378\tthrough the whole defended ASV pipeline.\n1379\tE. Adversarial example detection performance\n1380\tWe next investigate whether our purification methods can\n1381\talso be used for adversarial example detection. In this task, an\n1382\tinput utterance is classified as adversarial or genuine according\n1383\tto the ASV score difference before and after purification.\n1384\tIf this difference is large, the input is more likely to be\n1385\tadversarial. By setting a target false positive rate (FPR),\n1386\tdifferent decision thresholds can be obtained for different\n1387\tpurifiers.\n1388\tTable IV shows that this detection strategy works well for\n1389\tmost purifiers. The thresholds are computed on clean trials\n1390\tonly and then applied to 50-step PGD-ℓ2 adversarial trials\n1391\tfor detection. The best detection rate is achieved by PnP-\n1392\t\n1393\t\n1394\t=== PAGE 10 ===\n1395\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n1396\t10\n1397\tTABLE III\n1398\tADAPTIVE 50-STEP MI-FGSM ATTACK EVALUATION ON ECAPA-TDNN.\n1399\tWE REPORT THE EER OF ADAPTIVE EXAMPLES EVALUATED WITH THE\n1400\tSAME ATTACKED DEFENDER IN THE PIPELINE, TOGETHER WITH THE EER\n1401\tOF THE SAME EXAMPLES EVALUATED BY THE ASV ALONE.\n1402\tEER on adaptive examples\n1403\tAttacked Defender\n1404\twith defender\n1405\twithout defender\n1406\tNo defender\n1407\t–\n1408\t69.35\n1409\tAudioPure\n1410\t10.40\n1411\t8.60\n1412\tNoise-0.01\n1413\t41.60\n1414\t2.40\n1415\tPnP-Gaussian\n1416\t53.30\n1417\t1.20\n1418\tPnP-Diff\n1419\t11.15\n1420\t14.60\n1421\tPnP-Diff-2\n1422\t9.35\n1423\t2.70\n1424\tPnP-Diff + AudioPure\n1425\t11.95\n1426\t14.60\n1427\tPnP-Diff + DiffWavePnP\n1428\t20.60\n1429\t5.10\n1430\tTABLE IV\n1431\tADVERSARIAL EXAMPLE DETECTION RATE (DR) AT FPR=1% WITH THE\n1432\tABSOLUTE ASV SCORE DIFFERENCE BEFORE AND AFTER PURIFICATION.\n1433\tTHE 50-STEP PGD-ℓ2 EER IS SHOWN AS A REFERENCE FOR\n1434\tPURIFICATION PERFORMANCE UNDER THE SAME ATTACK SETTING.\n1435\t*MDD RESULT IS FROM THE ORIGINAL PAPER WITH THE SAME ATTACK.\n1436\tMethod\n1437\tDR(%)@FPR=1% ↑\n1438\tPGD EER (%) ↓\n1439\tMDD-10%*\n1440\t94.10\n1441\t18.00\n1442\tAudioPure\n1443\t94.75\n1444\t3.55\n1445\tNoise-0.01\n1446\t94.55\n1447\t3.35\n1448\tSpeechTokenizer\n1449\t95.95\n1450\t8.65\n1451\tPnP-Gaussian\n1452\t93.40\n1453\t6.15\n1454\tPnP-Diff\n1455\t96.60\n1456\t3.55\n1457\tPnP-Diff-2\n1458\t95.60\n1459\t3.40\n1460\tPnP-Diff + AudioPure\n1461\t96.60\n1462\t3.90\n1463\tPnP-Diff + DiffWavePnP\n1464\t94.70\n1465\t4.80\n1466\tDiff and PnP-Diff + AudioPure, both achieving 96.60% at\n1467\tFPR=1%. PnP-Gaussian gives the lowest detection rate among\n1468\tthe methods at 93.40%. This again shows that diffusion-style\n1469\tPnP variants provide a more stable detection cue than the\n1470\tadditive variant.\n1471\tIt is also useful to evaluate the detection and purification\n1472\tperformance jointly. Although Noise-0.01 achieves the lowest\n1473\t50-step PGD-ℓ2 EER of 3.35%, its detection rate is lower\n1474\tthan those of the diffusion-style methods. PnP-Diff achieves\n1475\tthe highest detection rate while maintaining a low EER of\n1476\t3.55%. We also compare with the previous MDD method with\n1477\ta 10% mask ratio [21]. Since MDD is specifically designed\n1478\tfor adversarial example detection rather than purification, its\n1479\tcorresponding PGD-ℓ2 EER remains as high as 18%. By\n1480\tcontrast, our method achieves strong performance on both\n1481\tpurification and detection.\n1482\tF. Impact on input: audio quality and intelligibility analysis\n1483\tIn this section, we also examine how purification alters the\n1484\tinput waveform itself. Table V and Table VI report objective\n1485\tspeech quality and intelligibility metrics, including WB-PESQ,\n1486\tSI-SDR, STOI, MOS-SSL, and WER, for selected waveform-\n1487\tdomain defenses. Table V reports the purification performance\n1488\tunder 50-step MI-FGSM attack on ECAPA-TDNN. We use\n1489\tWhisper to compute the WER between purified samples\n1490\t0\n1491\t20\n1492\t40\n1493\t60\n1494\t80\n1495\tFbank Bin\n1496\tClean\n1497\t0\n1498\t20\n1499\t40\n1500\t60\n1501\t80\n1502\tAttacked\n1503\t0\n1504\t20\n1505\t40\n1506\t60\n1507\t80\n1508\tPurified by AudioPure\n1509\t0\n1510\t20\n1511\