8\n1650\tAudioPure\n1651\t1.296\n1652\t14.93\n1653\t0.925\n1654\t2.011\n1655\t3.20\n1656\tNoise-0.01\n1657\t1.292\n1658\t14.87\n1659\t0.925\n1660\t1.999\n1661\t3.20\n1662\tSpeechTokenizer\n1663\t2.585\n1664\t1.42\n1665\t0.914\n1666\t3.885\n1667\t3.10\n1668\tPnP-Gaussian\n1669\t1.042\n1670\t-10.14\n1671\t0.612\n1672\t0.474\n1673\t6.58\n1674\tPnP-Diff\n1675\t1.431\n1676\t15.17\n1677\t0.943\n1678\t2.342\n1679\t3.14\n1680\tPnP-Diff-2\n1681\t1.096\n1682\t5.08\n1683\t0.847\n1684\t1.008\n1685\t3.23\n1686\tPnP-Diff + AudioPure\n1687\t1.437\n1688\t15.23\n1689\t0.944\n1690\t2.354\n1691\t3.02\n1692\tPnP-Diff + DiffWavePnP\n1693\t3.267\n1694\t23.32\n1695\t0.971\n1696\t3.634\n1697\t4.83\n1698\tDiffWave denoiser mainly serves as an extension for quality\n1699\tenhancement.\n1700\tFig. 6 provides a visual view of the Fbank features pu-\n1701\trified by selected diffusion-based methods. Compared with\n1702\tAudioPure, PnP-Diff produces similar features, and PnP-Diff\n1703\t+ DiffWavePnP yields the cleanest restoration among the\n1704\tcompared methods. The red-boxed region highlights a high-\n1705\tfrequency component that is almost removed by the other\n1706\tpurification methods but is more clearly preserved by PnP-\n1707\tDiff + DiffWavePnP. This suggests that the learned forward\n1708\tpurification is the main source of robustness, while the optional\n1709\tdenoising cascade can further improve perceptual fidelity\n1710\tand intelligibility. A full version of this visualization with\n1711\tall defenders in Table II is provided in the supplementary\n1712\tmaterial.\n1713\tG. Ablation study\n1714\tFinally, we perform ablation studies to understand which\n1715\tcomponents of the unified PnP framework are responsible\n1716\tfor the observed robustness gains. We first analyze the main\n1717\thyperparameters, then examine the effect of the purification\n1718\tstep, and finally test how PnP-Diff performs across different\n1719\tASV backbones.\n1720\t1) Effect of the main hyperparameters: We first examine\n1721\tthe effects of the regularization weight γ and the mixing factor\n1722\tλ on PnP-Diff and PnP-Gaussian. For both variants, we report\n1723\tthe purified EER on genuine unattacked inputs and adversarial\n1724\tinputs. As shown in Fig. 7, PnP-Diff is less sensitive to both γ\n1725\tand λ than PnP-Gaussian. In the γ study, γ = 10−2 provides\n1726\ta practical regularization trade-off by improving the stability\n1727\t0\n1728\t1e-2\n1729\t1e-1\n1730\tγ\n1731\t2\n1732\t4\n1733\t6\n1734\t8\n1735\t10\n1736\tEER (%)\n1737\tEffect of γ\n1738\tPnP-Gau. Gen\n1739\tPnP-Gau. Adv\n1740\tPnP-Diff Gen\n1741\tPnP-Diff Adv\n1742\t0.5\n1743\t0.7\n1744\t0.9\n1745\t1.0\n1746\tλ\n1747\t53.6*\n1748\t53.4*\n1749\tEffect of λ\n1750\tFig. 7. Ablation study on the main hyperparameters for PnP-Gaussian (PnP-\n1751\tGau.) and PnP-Diff. Solid lines denote adversarial EER and dashed lines\n1752\tdenote genuine EER after purification. * Values are outside the displayed y-\n1753\trange.\n1754\tof PnP-Gaussian without hurting the diffusion-style variant. In\n1755\tthe λ study, PnP-Diff remains within a relatively narrow EER\n1756\trange, whereas PnP-Gaussian performs best at λ = 0.7 and\n1757\tdegrades to random noising when λ = 1. Overall, λ = 0.7 or\n1758\t0.9 and γ = 10−2 provide a good trade-off.\n1759\t2) Effect of purification: We next examine how the purifica-\n1760\ttion step in PnP-Diff affects robustness. Fig. 8 compares the\n1761\t1-step AudioPure result with the 1-, 2-, and 3-step versions\n1762\tof PnP-Diff, as well as the sample-specific variant PnP-Diff-\n1763\tSSNI. The SSNI method [36] adaptively selects the purifica-\n1764\ttion step for each sample. We evaluate different purification\n1765\tsteps under three white-box attacks with different strengths.\n1766\tThe full numerical EER and RTF results are provided in the\n1767\t\n1768\t\n1769\t=== PAGE 12 ===\n1770\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n1771\t12\n1772\t5\n1773\t10\n1774\t20\n1775\t50\n1776\t100\n1777\t200\n1778\tIterations\n1779\t2.0\n1780\t2.5\n1781\t3.0\n1782\t3.5\n1783\t4.0\n1784\t4.5\n1785\tEER (%)\n1786\tMI-FGSM\n1787\tPnP-Diff-1\n1788\tPnP-Diff-2\n1789\tPnP-Diff-3\n1790\tPnP-Diff-SSNI\n1791\tAudioPure-1\n1792\t5\n1793\t10\n1794\t20\n1795\t50\n1796\t100\n1797\t200\n1798\tIterations\n1799\tPGD-L2\n1800\t5\n1801\t10\n1802\t20\n1803\t50\n1804\t100\n1805\t200\n1806\tIterations\n1807\tPGD-L∞\n1808\tFig. 8. Effect of purification step on ECAPA-TDNN against three white-box attacks. We compare 1-step AudioPure with the 1-, 2-, and 3-step PnP-Diff, and\n1809\tthe sample-specific variant PnP-Diff-SSNI. PnP-Diff-1 denotes the default PnP-Diff setting used in other tables. The x-axis shows the attack iteration number,\n1810\tand the y-axis reports the resulting EER (%) after purification.\n1811\tTABLE VII\n1812\tPNP-DIFF PURIFICATION RESULTS WITH EER (%) EVALUATED ON FOUR\n1813\tASV ARCHITECTURES UNDER 50-STEP MI-FGSM ATTACK.\n1814\tADVERSARIAL EXAMPLES ARE GENERATED SEPARATELY FOR EACH ASV.\n1815\t“GEN” AND “ADV” DENOTE GENUINE AND ADVERSARIAL EER AFTER\n1816\tPURIFICATION.\n1817\tASV architecture\n1818\tGen\n1819\tAdv\n1820\tECAPA-TDNN\n1821\t1.75\n1822\t4.45\n1823\tCAM++\n1824\t1.20\n1825\t2.90\n1826\tResNet\n1827\t1.00\n1828\t0.70\n1829\tSimAMResNet\n1830\t0.35\n1831\t0.70\n1832\tsupplementary material.\n1833\tFig. 8 shows that small purification steps are already suffi-\n1834\tcient for PnP-Diff. Across MI-FGSM, PGD-ℓ2, and PGD-ℓ∞\n1835\tattacks, the 1-step and 2-step variants cover most of the useful\n1836\trobustness range, while the 3-step variant is usually worse.\n1837\tPnP-Diff-SSNI is competitive and occasionally gives the best\n1838\tresult, but it does not provide a consistent improvement over\n1839\tthe fixed 1-step or 2-step settings. These results suggest that\n1840\ta small step is already effective.\n1841\t3) Effect across ASV backbones: As shown in Table VII, we\n1842\talso evaluate PnP-Diff on different ASV backbones to defend\n1843\tagainst 50-step MI-FGSM attacks. Although it is trained\n1844\ton adversarial examples generated from ECAPA-TDNN, it\n1845\tstill provides clear defensive gains for CAM++, ResNet,\n1846\tand SimAMResNet. This suggests that the learned π-noise\n1847\ttransfers well across different ASV architectures. In particular,\n1848\tfor ResNet, the EER for purified adversarial inputs is reduced\n1849\tto 0.70%, which is even lower than the EER for genuine inputs\n1850\tafter purification.\n1851\tVI. CONCLUSION\n1852\tThis paper proposes the Positive-Incentive Noise Predictor\n1853\t(PnP) framework, a simplification of previous noise-based and\n1854\tdiffusion-based audio adversarial purification methods. Our\n1855\tanalytics show that most robustness gains come from the\n1856\tforward noising stage. Based on this observation, we introduce\n1857\tpositive-incentive theory to learn an input-adaptive noising\n1858\tprocess as a front-end purifier. Within this framework, we\n1859\tstudy two variants: PnP-Gaussian, which serves as the simplest\n1860\tlearned additive-noising baseline, and PnP-Diff, which aligns\n1861\tthe learned π-noise with the diffusion forward noise schedule.\n1862\tBy combining PnP-Diff with a diffusion denoiser, we also\n1863\tprovide a diffusion model trained with learned π-noise for\n1864\tquality enhancement.\n1865\tThe experimental results demonstrate the effectiveness of\n1866\tthe proposed PnP methods. We compare the proposed methods\n1867\twith representative diffusion-based, additive-noise, and codec-\n1868\tbased purification baselines, and test all of them under white-\n1869\tbox and black-box attack settings. Under standard white-box\n1870\tattacks, the proposed PnP methods substantially reduce EERs\n1871\tfor adversarial inputs, and PnP-Diff provides the strongest\n1872\toverall balance between EERs for purified genuine inputs,\n1873\tadversarial robustness, and inference efficiency. In addition,\n1874\tPnP-Diff remains effective across four ASV backbones, while\n1875\tPnP-Diff-2 is more stable under a 50-step defender-aware\n1876\tadaptive MI-FGSM attack. Audio quality analysis further\n1877\tshows that diffusion-style variants preserve speech quality\n1878\tbetter than the simple additive variant, and that an optional\n1879\tdiffusion cascade can further improve waveform fidelity when\n1880\tperceptual quality is prioritized. In addition, PnP-Diff also\n1881\tperforms well on the adversarial example detection task. These\n1882\tresults indicate that learned forward noising is an appealing\n1883\talternative to full reverse diffusion for adversarial purification.\n1884\tREFERENCES\n1885\t[1] Z. Bai and X.-L. Zhang, “Speaker recognition based on deep learning:\n1886\tAn overview,” Neural Networks, vol. 140, pp. 65–99, 2021.\n1887\t[2] A. Baevski, Y. Zhou, A. Mohamed, and M. Auli, “wav2vec 2.0:\n1888\tA framework for self-supervised learning of speech representations,”\n1889\tAdvances in neural information processing systems, vol. 33, pp. 12 449–\n1890\t12 460, 2020.\n1891\t[3] S. Chen, C. Wang, Z. Chen, Y. Wu, S. Liu, Z. Chen, J. Li, N. Kanda,\n1892\tT. Yoshioka, X. Xiao et al., “Wavlm: Large-scale self-supervised pre-\n1893\ttraining for full stack speech processing,” IEEE Journal of Selected\n1894\tTopics in Signal Processing, vol. 16, no. 6, pp. 1505–1518, 2022.\n1895\t[4] A. Radford, J. W. Kim, T. Xu, G. Brockman, C. McLeavey, and\n1896\tI. Sutskever, “Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervi-\n1897\tsion,” in International conference on machine learning.\n1898\tPMLR, 2023,\n1899\tpp. 28 492–28 518.\n1900\t[5] X. Wang, H. Delgado, H. Tak, J.-w. Jung, H.-j. Shim, M. Todisco,\n1901\tI. Kukanov, X. Liu, M. Sahidullah, T. H. Kinnunen et al., “Asvspoof 5:\n1902\t\n1903\t\n1904\t=== PAGE 13 ===\n1905\tJOURNAL OF LATEX CLASS FILES, VOL. 14, NO. 8, AUGUST 2021\n1906\t13\n1907\tcrowdsourced speech data, deepfakes, and adversarial attacks at scale,”\n1908\tin Proc. ASVspoof 2024, 2024